# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2016-spanish-grand-prix
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] The **107% rule** is a sporting regulation affecting Formula One racing qualifying sessions.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] During the first phase of qualifying, if the circuit is dry, any driver who is eliminated in the first qualifying session and fails to set a lap within 107% of the fastest time in that session will not be allowed to start the race without permission from the race stewards.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] For example, if the fastest Q1 lap time was 100 seconds, each driver who is eliminated in the session must complete at least one lap within 107 seconds to guarantee a race start.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] The 107% rule was introduced for the 1996 season and remained in force until 2002.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] It was reintroduced for the 2011 season with minor modifications due to the knock-out qualifying format.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] The governing body of F1, the Fédération Internationale de l'Automobile (FIA), introduced the 107% rule at a meeting of its World Motor Sport Council in June 1995, immediately prior to the French Grand Prix.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] This followed a recommendation from the Formula One Commission, a working group of F1 representatives, to introduce such a measure.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Over the previous few years, the number of entries per season had dropped to 26, the maximum threshold for race starters, allowing every entrant to qualify for the race regardless of speed.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] For 1995, new technical regulations spaced out the field, whilst numerous teams with comparatively small budgets and slow cars, such as Forti, Pacific, and Simtek, were competing in the sport.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] The regulation was originally planned to come into effect from the 1995 Hungarian Grand Prix, but this required unanimous support amongst the teams, and was vetoed by Forti and Pacific.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Nevertheless, the fact that it was supported by the majority of the teams allowed the 107% rule's introduction from the start of the 1996 season.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] The mid-1990s also brought a number of pay drivers to the sport whose speeds would not have allowed them to race, such as Giovanni Lavaggi and Jean-Denis Delétraz.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Commenting on the introduction of the 107% rule, FIA President Max Mosley said that "any small team which is properly organised will be able to get within the 107 per cent margin".
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] The sport's commercial rights holder, Bernie Ecclestone, agreed with this sentiment, saying in an interview that "Formula 1 is the best.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] On the other hand, the smaller teams were concerned at the prospect of having to lap within a maximum time in order to qualify, which they saw as exacerbating the inequalities already existent within the sport.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Pacific's commercial manager, Mark Gallagher, said: "We have to say the 107% rule gives rise to concern among teams without works engines.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] It's got more to do with engines than chassis, and that's an area outside our direct capability.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Closing the gap to Minardi is quite feasible, but the sudden arrival of the rule is worrying.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] The 107% rule was thus introduced at the 1996 Australian Grand Prix.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] It was breached immediately, as Forti drivers Luca Badoer and Andrea Montermini failed to lap within 107% of Jacques Villeneuve's pole position time.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] This had been an expected outcome, as the team was using an upgraded version of the previous year's Forti FG01 chassis, which had only qualified within 107% of pole position on one of thirty-four occasions beforehand.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Both drivers also failed to qualify for the European Grand Prix, the fourth round of the championship.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] At the following race, the San Marino Grand Prix, Badoer drove the more competitive FG03 chassis for the first time, whilst Montermini failed to make the 107% cut in the older car.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Both then failed to qualify for the Spanish Grand Prix two races later.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] By the tenth round of the championship, the British Grand Prix, the team was running out of money and made only a token attempt to qualify after not taking part in the preceding free practice sessions, neither car making the time limit.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Following the next race, in which the team did not complete any laps at all, Forti withdrew from Formula One.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] In the latter half of the season, the Minardi team replaced regular driver Giancarlo Fisichella with the paying Giovanni Lavaggi, who failed to make the 107% cut at the German, Belgian, and Japanese Grands Prix.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] In 1997, the 107% rule was only invoked at the season-opening Australian Grand Prix.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Villeneuve again set pole position with a time over a second faster than his nearest rival, resulting in a well-spaced field.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] As a result, Pedro Diniz, Vincenzo Sospiri, and Ricardo Rosset all failed to make the 107% mark.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Diniz was allowed to race at the discretion of the race stewards, who judged him capable of lapping within the limit, as he had indeed done so during the free practice session prior to qualifying.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] The FIA cited "exceptional circumstances" as the reason for his failure to do so during the qualifying session itself.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Sospiri and Rosset, driving for the new MasterCard Lola team, were five and six seconds off Diniz's time respectively, and well outside the qualification limit.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Neither driver was allowed to start the race, and the team folded before the next Grand Prix.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] During the 1998 season, Rosset—now driving for the Tyrrell team—failed to qualify on five occasions.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] He lapped outside the 107% time during qualifying sessions for the Spanish, Monaco, Hungarian, and Japanese Grands Prix.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] He also failed to qualify for the German Grand Prix, but this was due to him not completing any laps at all after injuring his right elbow as a result of a heavy crash during free practice.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] The 107% rule was invoked on two occasions in 1999.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] At the first round of the championship—the Australian Grand Prix—Marc Gené failed to lap within the required percentage of the pole position time in his Minardi.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] As with Diniz two years earlier, he was given dispensation to race after lapping within the limit during the free practice sessions.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] At the French Grand Prix later in the season, a qualifying session marked by a varying intensity of rainfall saw five drivers—Damon Hill, Gené, Luca Badoer, Pedro de la Rosa, and Toranosuke Takagi—miss the cut-off, but all were allowed to start the race.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] After a 2000 season in which no driver transgressed the 107% rule, it was enforced on three occasions in 2001.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] At the opening race in Australia, Tarso Marques failed to lap within the required time for Minardi.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] He was given permission to race under the reason of "exceptional circumstances", but this was despite the fact that he had not managed to set a time within the 107% mark in any session all weekend.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] It was rumoured that Marques was allowed to race because the team had been bought prior to the start of the season by Australian Paul Stoddart, who wanted both cars to compete in Minardi's new "home" Grand Prix.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] At the British Grand Prix, Marques again fell foul of the regulation, but was not allowed to start on this occasion.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] The Belgian Grand Prix also witnessed a wet qualifying session in which the track steadily dried, resulting in the four slowest qualifiers—Jos Verstappen, Fernando Alonso, Enrique Bernoldi, and Marques—failing to lap within 107% of pole position.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] As in the similar case of the French Grand Prix two years previously, all were allowed to start the race.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] The 107% rule also came into effect during the 2002 season.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] At the first round of the championship, the Australian Grand Prix, Takuma Sato crashed heavily during free practice and had to use the Jordan team's spare car for qualifying, only for the replacement to stop with a gearbox problem without setting a time.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] By the time his teammate, Fisichella, did his first run and handed over his own chassis, it had begun to rain, leaving Sato with no chance of making the required time.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] However, he was allowed to start the race as in the case of previous cases affected by changeable weather conditions.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Minardi driver Alex Yoong failed to qualify for the San Marino, British, and German Grands Prix under the conditions of the rule, a turn of events which led to his replacement by Anthony Davidson for two races.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] At the French Grand Prix, the Arrows team was running out of money and made a token appearance during the qualifying session to avoid FIA-imposed fines for missing rounds of the championship; drivers Heinz-Harald Frentzen and Bernoldi failed to lap within the required time.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Frentzen subsequently left the circuit with ten minutes of the session still remaining, making the team's ploy obvious.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Fisichella also failed to qualify as he did not set a time during this session, although this was the result of his withdrawal from the event following a heavy crash during free practice.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] In total, there were 37 cases in which the 107% rule was broken during the period in which it was a Formula One Sporting Regulation.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Of these, 13 drivers were allowed to start the relevant race due to "exceptional circumstances".
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] The rule affected 23 out of the 116 Grands Prix in which it applied.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] The qualifying system changed for the 2003 season with the introduction of two ordered single-lap sessions to replace the previous free hour-long session in which drivers were allowed to complete twelve laps.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Drivers also had to qualify with the race fuel on board their cars.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Due to the scope for greater time disparities throughout the field that could occur as a result, the 107% rule was not mentioned when the FIA finalised the format prior to the beginning of the season, despite an earlier assurance that the rule would still apply.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] The governing body subsequently proposed the formal cancellation of the rule, which ceased to apply with effect from the 2002 Japanese Grand Prix.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Following the 2003 season, the timing of the two single-lap sessions was altered for them to occur on the same day, within 15 minutes of each other.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] During the 2004 season, the system's flaws were exposed, and proposed changes to the qualifying system made midway through the championship at one point seemed to suggest that the 107% rule would return as part of a new format.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] In the end, however, only minor changes relating to the timing of the existing sessions were made.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Minardi team owner Paul Stoddart was particularly opposed to the reintroduction of the rule.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] At the start of the 2010 season, new FIA President Jean Todt said that he was in favour of re-introducing the 107% rule, as the qualifying system had changed again so that all of the sessions were carried out with low fuel levels.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] On 23 June, a meeting of the FIA World Motor Sport Council determined that the 107% rule would be reintroduced for the 2011 season.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] The rule applies only to the first of the three qualifying sessions for each race.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] From its re-introduction to the end of the 2015 season, the 107% rule was broken a further 17 times at 12 different races, all but one by HRT, Caterham, and Virgin/Marussia drivers.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Unlike the rule's first period of application, where infringing drivers were very rarely allowed to compete, only four of these occurrences of rule violation resulted in the drivers being barred from the race.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] These were Vitantonio Liuzzi and Narain Karthikeyan at the 2011 Australian Grand Prix, and Pedro de la Rosa and Karthikeyan at the 2012 Australian Grand Prix – all of whom drove for HRT.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] At the 2016 Hungarian Grand Prix, eleven drivers failed to reach the 107% limit as the session was stopped for inclement weather and subsequent incidents, but all were permitted to compete.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Beginning with the 2018 season, the regulations were amended so that the 107% rule would not be enforced if the track was declared wet by the race director during qualifying.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] The 107% rule, or variations thereof, has also been used in other motorsport series.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Formula E applies an alternative 110% rule in qualifying.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Race stewards have discretion to allow drivers who broke the rule to partake in the race, usually by looking at the times posted in free practice sessions.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] The rule is most commonly broken when a driver fails to enter his qualifying lap in time or has had his qualifying lap invalidated (therefore only his entry lap is recorded).
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] The car breaking down or a crash during the session could also lead to a violation of this rule.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] There has been no occasion where a driver was not allowed to compete in the race so far.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] The 107% rule is also used in the GP2 Series as well as its successor Formula 2, where it has been applied on four occasions.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Marcos Martínez failed to qualify for his debut race meeting at the Hungaroring in 2007 after failing to set a lap time due to engine problems, despite lapping within 107% of the fastest time in free practice.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] At the Monaco round of the 2009 season, Ricardo Teixeira failed to lap within 107% of the pole position time and was not allowed to take part in the races.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Perera also failed to qualify for the Spa-Francorchamps races under the 107% criteria.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Alessio Deledda became the first driver since Perera in this racing category to fall victim to the 107% rule.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] He qualified 6.341 seconds off from the fastest time set by Robert Shwartzman in his group during qualifying for the Monaco Grand Prix round in 2021.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] As he was 7.314 seconds off the fastest time set by Shwartzman during the practice session, he was unable to take part in all three races in the weekend.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] He was, however, given permission to start by the stewards, after it was later revealed after the weekend that Deledda's car had mechanical problems and that he was within the 107% time during the previous round at Bahrain.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] The 107% rule is also used in the GP3 Series and the succeeding Formula 3.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] So far, the rule has only been in effect on one occasion during the GP3 era.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] In the 2012 Silverstone round, Carmen Jordá failed to set a lap time within 107% of the pole time.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] As she was also outside 107% of the fastest time in the practice session, she was not allowed to start the race.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] MotoGP uses a similar rule for race competition, where riders must be within 105% of the lap times of the fastest rider in each of the practice sessions in order to take part in qualifying sessions.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Between 2013 and 2021, the 107% rule was also used in the competition.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Riders including Aleix Espargaro and Cal Crutchlow criticized about the effectiveness of the rule when Christophe Ponsson finished one lap slower than the race winner in 2018 San Marino Grand Prix, urging the FIM to tighten the rule.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Japanese rider Takumi Takahashi, who won Suzuka 8 Hours in 2010, failed to qualify in 2023 San Marino motorcycle Grand Prix after running 0.6 slower than the 105% of the fastest lap time in practice sessions.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] The IndyCar Series uses a similar rule for race competition, where cars must be within 105% of the lap times of the fastest car.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] NASCAR uses a similar rule for race competition, where cars must be within 115% of the fastest lap set in the final practice.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] In Super GT series, a slightly different 107% rule is being used.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Until 2024, the base time is calculated by the mean time of top three cars within a class rather than the fastest lap time by a single car in that class.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] All drivers in the non-seeded teams must set a lap time within this time in order to qualify for the race.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] However, teams which could not qualify in official qualifying sessions may still be allowed to retry in following day's practice session, providing reasons such as accidents.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] In this case, the 107% of top three cars in practice session's will be used instead, in return, teams will start at the back of the grid.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] In races using the knockout format, a separate qualifying session will be launched prior the knockout qualifying to decide teams which are allowed to take part in the race.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] From 2024, this was removed from Q1 lap times and only applied to Q2 laps.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] Another major difference of the 107% rule in Super GT is that there is a protection system called "seeded teams", which is awarded to each team which participated in all races and finished within the top 12 of its class in the previous season.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] These teams, provided they meet other entrance requirements, are allowed to participate in all races even when they fail to meet the qualifying time in official qualifying sessions.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] A team's "seeded team" status is forfeited when the team switches class or withdraws from the series, and the void caused by this will not be filled in by other teams.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] The World Rally-Raid Championship used a 107% rule to set the starting lineup for the first stage of a given rally.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] If a driver regardless of category set a time within 107% of the prologue's winner, they were to start ahead of those with slower times for the next day.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] This percentage expanded to 115% for drivers with a gold or platinum FIA Driver Categorisation.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/107-rule] In mid-2026, the percentage was increased to 117%.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] The **2007 Japanese Grand Prix** (officially the **2007 Formula 1 Fuji Television Japanese Grand Prix**) was a Formula One motor race held on 30 September 2007 at the Fuji Speedway, Oyama, Shizuoka.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] The 67-lap race was the fifteenth round of the 2007 FIA Formula One World Championship.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] It was held at the recently revised track in very heavy rain and misty conditions.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] For the previous 20 years, the Japanese Grand Prix had been held at Suzuka Circuit, but at this race it returned to Fuji for the first time since 1977.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] The very wet race was won by McLaren driver Lewis Hamilton, who also took pole position and the fastest lap of the race.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Heikki Kovalainen achieved his first podium, by finishing second for the Renault team (Renault's only podium that year), whilst Kimi Räikkönen finished in third for Ferrari.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Adrian Sutil scored his first point and Spyker's first and only point by finishing ninth and being promoted to eighth after the race following a penalty for Vitantonio Liuzzi.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] As a consequence of the race, Hamilton extended his lead in the World Drivers' Championship to twelve points over McLaren teammate Fernando Alonso.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Alonso had only been two points behind Hamilton in the standings before he crashed during the race.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Räikkönen's third-place finish ensured he remained in mathematical contention to clinch the drivers' title in the remaining two rounds.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] His Ferrari teammate, Felipe Massa, dropped out of championship contention after finishing the race in sixth position.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Massa was now ten points behind Räikkönen.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] In the World Constructors' Championship, Ferrari were leading the standings on 170 points.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] McLaren would have been leading the table on 202 points had they not been given a penalty in the Hungarian Grand Prix, and then disqualified entirely due to the espionage controversy that year.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] BMW Sauber remained second in the standings, 78 points behind Ferrari, after scoring just two points in the race.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Renault ensured that they would finish the year in third, (like BMW Sauber, they were unpassable by any other team), and were 41 points behind.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Lewis Hamilton of McLaren led the Drivers' Championship by two points from his team-mate Fernando Alonso, who was a further 11 points ahead of Ferrari's Kimi Räikkönen.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] After McLaren's exclusion from the Constructors' Championship, Ferrari had been confirmed as Constructors' Champions, following their Belgian Grand Prix one-two.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] They were 71 points ahead of BMW Sauber.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Three Japanese constructors and two Japanese drivers competed in the race.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Toyota were 6th in the Constructors' Championship, whilst Honda were 8th, behind their own "B-team" Super Aguri.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Takuma Sato was 15th in the Drivers' Championship for Super Aguri, whilst compatriot Sakon Yamamoto had yet to score for Spyker F1, having debuted at the Hungarian Grand Prix.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] David Coulthard changed his helmet design for this race, choosing to use the helmet design of former World Rally Champion Colin McRae, who had died two weeks before the race in a helicopter crash.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] As with the 2006 race, the event was filmed and broadcast in high-definition by Fuji Television for the domestic Japanese audience.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Although the weather had dried out by the time qualifying began, the track was still wet and all the drivers went out on wet tyres.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Qualifying one saw the two Spykers of Adrian Sutil and Sakon Yamamoto and the two Super Aguris of Anthony Davidson and Takuma Sato eliminated, along with Alexander Wurz in the Williams and Rubens Barrichello in the Honda.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Ralf Schumacher's Toyota also collided with Yamamoto, forcing both drivers out of qualifying.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Schumacher was already through to Q2, but could not set a time in the second session and so qualified 16th.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Qualifying two saw the elimination of the two Renaults of Giancarlo Fisichella and Heikki Kovalainen, David Coulthard's Red Bull, Vitantonio Liuzzi's Toro Rosso and the Toyotas of Jarno Trulli and Schumacher.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Sebastian Vettel in the Toro Rosso and Robert Kubica in the BMW Sauber occupied row 5, just behind Jenson Button, getting his best qualifying of the season in the Honda, and Mark Webber's Red Bull.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Nico Rosberg qualified 6th in the Williams, but was penalised ten places for an engine change.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] This meant that Vettel qualified eighth, the then best qualifying ever for Toro Rosso.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Nick Heidfeld qualified 5th for BMW Sauber, and the top four was once again the two McLarens and two Ferraris.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] The Ferraris failed to get on the front row, with Kimi Räikkönen and Felipe Massa 3rd and 4th respectively.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Lewis Hamilton then pipped his more experienced McLaren teammate Fernando Alonso to earn the fifth pole position of his career.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Due to torrential rainfall, the race was started behind the safety car, which led the field for the first 19 laps.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] The Ferraris of Kimi Räikkönen and Felipe Massa were forced to pit during the first few laps after starting on standard wet tyres, as opposed to "extreme wet" tyres, which were better-suited to the treacherously wet conditions.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Ferrari boss Jean Todt later stated that the team were not informed about the requirements prior to the race, although all other teams were.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] During the initial safety car period, the FIA instructed the lapped driver Vitantonio Liuzzi to pass the field and catch up to the back of the queue as quickly as he safely could, as a way of gauging whether the track was ready for the race to begin in earnest.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] The Ferraris dropped back to 20th and 21st positions respectively following the pit stops, and Massa pitted again on lap 15.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] When the safety car finally left the circuit, the two McLarens began the race proper at the head of the field, in front of the quick-starting Sebastian Vettel.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] The Toro Rosso driver had taken third place from Nick Heidfeld, after the latter and Jenson Button's Honda collided.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Mark Webber was in fourth by the first racing lap as a result of the collision, despite still suffering from the after-effects of food poisoning, having earlier vomited into his helmet during the first safety car period.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] A first-corner spin caused Alexander Wurz to collide heavily with Felipe Massa's Ferrari.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Wurz's car sustained heavy damage and he retired on the spot.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Later in the race, Fernando Alonso crashed out, later blaming aquaplaning for the accident, which once again brought out the safety car.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] It was the first time that a McLaren car had failed to finish during the 2007 season.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] During this safety car period on lap 45, third-placed Sebastian Vettel crashed into the rear of second-placed Webber in the wet conditions, Webber retiring immediately and Vettel returning to the pits to retire.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Vettel had earlier became the youngest ever driver to lead a lap of a Formula One race (aged 20 years and 89 days) – his record was subsequently broken by Max Verstappen (aged 18 years and 228 days) at the 2016 Spanish Grand Prix.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] The collision put Heikki Kovalainen's Renault in second place, which he managed to hold until the end of the race, despite repeated overtaking attempts by Kimi Räikkönen.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] It was Kovalainen's first podium finish.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Räikkönen would eventually finish third, ahead of David Coulthard in fourth for Red Bull Racing.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] This was the first time that two Finnish drivers had both finished on the podium.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] On the final lap, Felipe Massa prevailed in his battle with BMW driver Robert Kubica.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] The Pole had previously served a drive through penalty for colliding with Hamilton.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Massa finished sixth, and Kubica seventh, behind Giancarlo Fisichella's Renault.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Vitantonio Liuzzi finished in eighth, scoring the first 2007 championship points for Toro Rosso.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] However, these points were later removed when Liuzzi was penalised for overtaking Adrian Sutil under waved yellow flags.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] This promoted Sutil to eighth, giving him and the Spyker team their first and only F1 points.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Hamilton was leading the race right in front of Webber, before suddenly braking and forcing Webber to follow suit lest he be penalised for overtaking behind the safety car, potentially causing Vettel's car to run into the back of Webber.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Hamilton might have faced either disqualification or a grid penalty for the next race, but the FIA decided not to impose any penalty.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] The event was afflicted by poor transportation, poor facilities (including some reserved seats without a view), a lack of organization, and expensive meals that meant a simple lunch-box was sold for 10,000 yen (US$87) at the circuit.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] The free practice session on Saturday was abandoned after repeated delays due to fog, which grounded the medical helicopter.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Only three drivers set a time in four minutes: Alexander Wurz (Williams-Toyota), Nico Rosberg (Williams-Toyota) and Jarno Trulli (Toyota).
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Before the race, there were suggestions that the plan of carrying all of the 100,000 or more spectators only by shuttle bus would be impossible.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] To relieve people's doubts, the circuit announced that there was complete preparation for the race.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] These doubts were realised when, after the qualifying session on Saturday, the shuttle buses could not leave because the road on the east gate of the circuit sank around 16:00.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] As a result, approximately 20,000 spectators were forced to stay for four hours or more until 21:00.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] For the race on Sunday, only the shuttle bus was admitted for spectators as transport.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] On Sunday morning, the circuit announced that they would refund spectators who had bought seats in the reserved seat area on 'C' stand, near the first corner.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] This was due to the low visibility which meant that the cars on the racing line were not seen at all.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] The cost of the tickets, 50,000 yen (US$435), was scheduled to be reimbursed to 7,000 people who were in the stand.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] The total cost of the refund was expected to be around 350 million yen (US$3 million).
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] After the race on Sunday, the circuit held a press conference to apologise for problems and announced that they would refund another 85 spectators who did not arrive at the circuit until after the start of the race due to the delay of the shuttle bus.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] The circuit said that they would reimburse them for all the costs caused by watching the race: the transportation expenses, the hotel charges and the cost of the tickets.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Fuji Speedway prohibited spectators from setting up flags and banners supporting teams and drivers, with the exception of the Toyota F1 team whose owner also owned the circuit.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] Therefore, there were very few flags and banners in the event compared with other Grand Prix events.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] After the event, Japanese media figures such as Fuji TV F1 commentator Jun Imamiya, and Fuji TV F1 commentator and former mechanic for Benetton Formula Tetsuo Tsugawa criticised the organization of the circuit.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] However, the event was well received by visitors in the paddock.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] In 2009, the Japanese Grand Prix was held again at Suzuka, with the plan to alternate between the two circuits in subsequent years.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] It was suggested that this could help to prevent future shows of such flagrant parochialism.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] However, Toyota later announced that the Japanese Grand Prix would not be held at Fuji Speedway any more, and the 2008 Japanese Grand Prix was the last held at the circuit.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2007-japanese-grand-prix] On 16 June 2008, 109 spectators went to Tokyo District Court and took an action against the circuit to claim total 32 million yen (US$295,500) in compensation for bad health and missing the race due to the problems with the shuttle buses.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] The **2008 Italian Grand Prix** (formally the **Formula 1 Gran Premio Santander D'Italia 2008**) was a Formula One motor race held on 14 September 2008 at the Autodromo Nazionale di Monza, Monza, Italy.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] It was the 14th race of the 2008 Formula One World Championship.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Future four-time World Champion Sebastian Vettel for the Toro Rosso team took a maiden victory, winning the 53-lap race from a maiden pole position.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Heikki Kovalainen finished second in a McLaren, and Robert Kubica third in a BMW Sauber.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Vettel began the race, started under the safety car, ahead of Kovalainen in second.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Red Bull's Mark Webber started from third.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Rain early in the race allowed Vettel to establish a solid lead over Kovalainen, which he extended as the track dried.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Kubica and Fernando Alonso finished in the top four after starting from 11th and eighth, respectively.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] McLaren driver and Drivers' Championship leader Lewis Hamilton was able to move through the field after qualifying in 15th, finishing in seventh, one place behind rival Felipe Massa, of Ferrari.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Vettel's record was broken by Max Verstappen aged 18 years and 228 days at the 2016 Spanish Grand Prix.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Massa scored one point more than Hamilton, narrowing the McLaren driver's lead in the Championship once more with four races remaining.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] However, Kovalainen's second-placed finish put McLaren closer to catching Ferrari in the Constructors' Championship.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Heading into the 14th race of the season, McLaren driver Lewis Hamilton led the Drivers' Championship with 76 points; Ferrari driver Felipe Massa was second on 74 points, two points behind Hamilton.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Behind Hamilton and Massa in the Drivers' Championship, Robert Kubica was third on 58 points in a BMW Sauber, and Massa's Ferrari teammate Kimi Räikkönen fourth on 57 points.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Kubica's teammate Nick Heidfeld was fifth on 49 points.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] In the Constructors' Championship, Ferrari were leading on 131 points and McLaren were second on 119 points, 12 points behind.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] In the battle for fourth-place Toyota had 41 points, ahead of Renault with 36 points.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] After the previous race, Hamilton was penalised for cutting a chicane and gaining an advantage over Räikkönen in the closing laps.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] This meant that Hamilton was demoted from first to third position, giving victory to Massa.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] While McLaren had lodged an appeal against the decision, the result would not be heard until September 23.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Testing at the Monza circuit in early September had indicated that the performance gap between McLaren and Ferrari had narrowed.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Despite this, Ferrari were hoping that their straight-line speed would be better suited to Monza's long straights.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Ferrari confirmed on September 12 that Räikkönen would continue to drive for the team until at least 2010, ending media speculation that he could be about to retire.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Three practice sessions were held before the race: the first was held on Friday morning and the second on Friday afternoon.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] The third session was held on Saturday morning and lasted an hour.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] All three sessions were affected by rain, with only the second giving teams any chance to run dry-weather tyres.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Adrian Sutil was quickest with a time of 1:32.842 in the first session, more than half a second quicker than the next fastest drivers Rubens Barrichello and Giancarlo Fisichella.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Timo Glock was the next quickest, almost four seconds behind Sutil.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Conditions were so poor that six drivers, including both McLarens, failed to set times.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] The session was stopped four minutes early, though by that time no cars had entered the track for at least ten minutes.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] The track dried out in the second session; Räikkönen adapted best to the changed conditions with a lap of 1:23.861, significantly quicker than his morning time.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Kubica was the next fastest, with his BMW teammate Heidfeld in third.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Hamilton, Nico Rosberg and Massa rounded out the top six.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Glock was fastest in the final session with a time of 1:35.464, followed by Sebastian Vettel, Rosberg, Jarno Trulli, Kazuki Nakajima and Heidfeld.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Hamilton only completed eight laps, and finished last with a time almost 11 seconds behind Glock.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] The qualifying session on Saturday afternoon was split into three parts.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] The first part ran for 20 minutes and eliminated the cars from qualifying that finished the session 16th or lower.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] The second part of qualifying lasted 15 minutes and eliminated cars that finished in positions 11 to 15.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] The final part of qualifying determined the positions from first to tenth, and decided pole position.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Cars which competed in the final session of qualifying were not allowed to refuel before the race, and as such carried more fuel than in the previous sessions.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Vettel became the youngest driver in the history of Formula One to take pole position, with a time of 1:37.555 in very wet conditions.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] He was joined on the front row of the grid by Kovalainen.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Mark Webber qualified third after his final lap pushed Sébastien Bourdais into fourth position.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Massa took sixth position behind Rosberg.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Trulli, Fernando Alonso, Glock and Heidfeld rounded out the top ten.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Kubica qualified 11th, blaming late rain in the second qualifying session for his position.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Fisichella qualified 12th to give Force India its best grid position of the season.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Both Räikkönen and Hamilton blamed a late entry into the second session for their poor qualifying times, which saw them eliminated in 14th and 15th positions, respectively.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Hamilton originally ran on the standard wet-weather tyres, and by the time he had changed to extreme wet-weather tyres the rain had intensified.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] This was McLaren's only result outside the top ten in qualifying all season and the first time in Hamilton's career that he had failed to progress into the final qualifying session.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Heavy rain prior to the race made the track very slippery, with more rain expected throughout the day.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] The air temperature at the track was 14 °C (57 °F).
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Jenson Button and Kazuki Nakajima started the race from the pit-lane, their teams choosing to make adjustments from qualifying to the set-ups of their cars.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] All cars were using extreme wet-weather tyres.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] The race began at 14:00 local time (UTC+1) behind the safety car because of the rain, meaning that there would be a rolling start.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Bourdais' car stalled on the grid, and was pushed back to the pits.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] By the time his team restarted the car, he was in last position and one lap down.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] The safety car pulled into the pit-lane at the end of the second lap.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Vettel retained his lead into the first corner, followed by Kovalainen, Webber, Rosberg and Massa.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Kubica passed Heidfeld at the first chicane; Glock passed Alonso later in the lap.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Vettel immediately opened a lead of two seconds over Kovalainen; the McLaren driver experienced visibility problems as a result of the spray off the back of the Toro Rosso.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Alonso regained seventh from Glock when he passed him at the first chicane on lap four as the track began to dry.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Räikkönen and Hamilton passed Coulthard on the same lap to take 12th and 13th positions, respectively.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] The next lap, Hamilton attempted to pass Räikkönen at the third corner, but overshot, cutting the chicane.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Emerging ahead of the Ferrari, he gave the place back, returning the advantage and avoiding a penalty.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Glock spun on lap seven, losing one place to Kubica.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Vettel continued to open his lead on Kovalainen; by lap eight it stood at 6.3 seconds.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Both Räikkönen and Hamilton passed Fisichella in separate manoeuvres over the next two laps.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Hamilton took 11th position from Räikkönen on lap 11, outbraking the Ferrari at turn four.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Fisichella collided with Coulthard two laps later.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] As a result of the contact, the Force India's front wing broke loose and lodged under the car.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Consequently, Fisichella lost control at turn nine, spinning into the gravel trap and retiring.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Massa overtook Rosberg for fourth on the same lap, beginning a close fight where both drivers repeatedly exchanged positions over the next three laps.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Massa eventually consolidated fourth position on lap 15.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Hamilton passed Heidfeld, Glock, Kubica and Alonso in separate manoeuvres, to sit in seventh by lap 19.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Vettel pitted from first position on lap 18.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Kovalainen, Webber and Massa pitted four laps later.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Light rain began to fall on lap 26, though only lasted five minutes.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Glock, Trulli, Räikkönen and Hamilton completed their first pit stops over the following laps.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Coulthard was the first driver to try intermediate wet-weather tyres when he pitted on lap 28.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] He lost grip in the wet and went straight through the first chicane.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Alonso, Heidfeld, Kubica and Piquet took their only pit stops for the race soon after, all changing to intermediate tyres.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] By lap 36 the majority of the field were running on intermediate tyres.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Webber was passed at turn eight by Massa on lap 35.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] The Australian spun after the corner, though managed to retain seventh position.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] A lap later, however, Hamilton outbraked Webber at turn three and demoted the Red Bull driver to eighth.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Hamilton began lapping fastest, recording a 1:32.869 on lap 38, more than a second faster than first-placed Vettel.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Lap 45 saw three drivers set consecutive new fastest laps; Kubica's 1:32.366 was beaten by Webber with a 1:32.014s.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] They were then superseded by Räikkönen, who set a 1:31.691.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] On lap 49 Webber attempted to pass Hamilton at the first chicane, but the two cars touched wheels.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Webber was forced down the escape road, and when he emerged in front of Hamilton, he returned the position.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Räikkönen continued to move through the field; he passed Coulthard and Piquet in separate manoeuvres to take ninth position.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Nakajima attempted to pass Coulthard into turn nine, but succeeded only in turning into the Red Bull RB4, sending it into the gravel trap.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Coulthard pitted for a new front wing, which dropped him to 17th.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Vettel crossed the finish line on lap 53 by 12.5 seconds over Kovalainen, becoming the youngest driver in Formula One history to win a Grand Prix.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] The one-stop strategies used by Kubica and Alonso paid off as they finished in third and fourth, respectively.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Heidfeld, Massa, Hamilton and Webber rounded out the top eight.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Räikkönen finished in ninth position, setting the fastest laptime of 1:28.047 on the final lap.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] The top three finishers appeared on the podium and in the subsequent press conference.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Vettel acknowledged the support of his team, saying the set-up of the car perfectly suited the way the race developed.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Other drivers congratulated Vettel; Hamilton said that "with all that pressure it is easier to make mistakes, and he obviously didn't, so congratulations to him.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] He did a good job." The Grand Prix also marked the first win by Toro Rosso, the first non-Ferrari Italian-based team to win since 1957.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Many of the Toro Rosso team had been there when the outfit competed as Minardi, a team that rarely scored points, let alone won a race, but were always very popular, adding an emotional aspect to the victory.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Kovalainen's second-placed finish closed the gap in the Constructors' Championship between Ferrari and McLaren from twelve to five points.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] Third-placed Kubica said that his strategy allowed him to capitalise on the changing track conditions, as his only stop seemed the best time to change to intermediate tyres.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] The Polish driver said that racing in Italy was particularly special for him, having lived in the country for five years: "That is why we divided the helmet into two pieces.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2008-italian-grand-prix] One was Italian colours, one was Polish colours." Alonso, who used a similar strategy, said "the result today is very good because Monza was supposed to be the race that we were looking forward to the least." Toyota's failure to score at the race meant that they were tied with Renault on 41 points.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The **2010 Abu Dhabi Grand Prix** (formally the **2010 Formula 1 Etihad Airways Abu Dhabi Grand Prix**) was a Formula One motor race held on 14 November 2010 at the Yas Marina Circuit on Yas Island, an island on the outskirts of Abu Dhabi in the United Arab Emirates.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] It was the nineteenth and final round of the 2010 Formula One season.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The 55-lap race was won by Red Bull driver Sebastian Vettel after starting from pole position.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Lewis Hamilton finished second in a McLaren, and teammate Jenson Button completed the podium, in third place.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Button's third place allowed him to finish fifth in the championship standings, having been eliminated from championship contention at the previous race in Brazil.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Due to injuries sustained in a rally crash prior to the 2011 Formula One season, this was the last Formula One race for Robert Kubica until the 2019 Australian Grand Prix.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] This was also the last Grand Prix for Lucas di Grassi and Christian Klien.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] This event also notably marked the last race for Bridgestone as a tyre supplier in Formula One, since their full time debut in 1997.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Pirelli became the sole tyre supplier for all teams in 2011, entering the sport for the first time since 1991.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Heading into the final race of the season, Ferrari driver Fernando Alonso was leading the Drivers' Championship with 246 points; Red Bull drivers Mark Webber and Sebastian Vettel were second and third on 238 points and 231 points respectively.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] McLaren's Lewis Hamilton was also in mathematical contention on 222 points, 24 behind Alonso with a maximum of 25 points available for the final race.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] As a result, this was the first occasion that four drivers still had a chance of winning the Drivers' Championship at the final event of the season.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] In the Constructors' Championship, Red Bull Racing had already secured their first championship title with a total of 469 points, 48 clear of second-placed McLaren with a maximum of 43 points available.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] McLaren were themselves not confirmed in second place in the championship, with a 32-point advantage over Ferrari.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Much of the media coverage occurring before the event was centred upon Red Bull, and the possibility of team orders being used to influence the result of the championship – if the team was in the position to do so – as had been used by Ferrari at the German Grand Prix.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] During that race, Ferrari had used radio transmissions to organize for Fernando Alonso to overtake teammate Felipe Massa for the race victory and gain seven extra points towards the Drivers' Championship.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Team owner Dietrich Mateschitz and team principal Christian Horner both stated that Red Bull would not impose any team orders in order to benefit one of its drivers in a bid to stop Alonso from winning the championship.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Sebastian Vettel himself had stated that he would help his teammate win the championship if required, having trailed Mark Webber by seven points heading into the weekend.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] After 242 races since their full-time return in 1997, tyre supplier Bridgestone bowed out of Formula One, having been the sport's single tyre supplier since Michelin pulled out after the 2006 season.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Pirelli took over the tyre contract in 2011, returning to Formula One for the first time since 1991.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Webber and Vettel both had an opportunity to win their first title at this event, and Red Bull's first ever Drivers' Championship since it purchased the former Jaguar F1 Team in 2005, while Hamilton and Alonso had the opportunity to win their second and third Drivers' title, respectively.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Furthermore, Webber and Vettel would have been the first World Drivers' Champions for their respective countries since Alan Jones and Michael Schumacher, while Vettel also had the chance of being the youngest ever World Champion, aged 23 years and 134 days.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Reigning World Drivers' Champion Jenson Button was mathematically eliminated from championship contention as he was unable to overcome a 47-points-deficit heading into the final round of the season.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Three practice sessions were held before the race; the first on Friday afternoon and the second on Friday evening.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The third session was held on Saturday afternoon and lasted an hour.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] All three sessions were held in dry conditions, although the first session was held on a damp but drying track after a pre-session downpour which had not been anticipated.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Vettel was quickest with a time of 1:42.760 in the first session, just over six-tenths of a second faster than Hamilton.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Button was another four-tenths off Hamilton's pace, followed by Webber, Robert Kubica, and Alonso.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Michael Schumacher was seventh, the only other driver to be within 1.5 seconds of Vettel's time.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] In the second practice session, Hamilton was fastest with a time of 1:40.888, around a quarter of a second quicker than second-placed Vettel.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Alonso took third place, ahead of Webber, Kubica and Felipe Massa.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Schumacher was only quick enough for eleventh position in the session, marginally slower than his Mercedes teammate Nico Rosberg.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The Saturday afternoon session was held on a much warmer track, which reached temperatures as high as 43 °C (109 °F), compared with 29 °C (84 °F) and 31 °C (88 °F) track temperatures for the Friday sessions.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Vettel was again quickest, posting a time of 1:40.696, narrowly faster than teammate Webber.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Hamilton, Alonso, Button and Vitaly Petrov rounded out the top six positions.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The qualifying session held on Saturday evening was split into three parts.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The first part ran for 20 minutes and eliminated the cars from qualifying that finished the session 18th or lower.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The second part of qualifying lasted 15 minutes and eliminated cars that finished in positions 11 to 17.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Cars which competed in the final session of qualifying were not allowed to change tyres before the race, and as such started the race on the tyres that they set their quickest lap on.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] , following the third qualifying session, in which he qualified the farthest back of the four title contenders, in fifth.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Vettel clinched his tenth pole position for the season, with a time of 1:39.394.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] As a result, Vettel became only the seventh driver to record ten pole positions in a season, and took his team's 15th pole of the season, equalling McLaren's tally from the 1988 season.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] He was joined on the front row of the grid by Hamilton.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Alonso qualified third, though he was happy with his grid position having outqualified Webber.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Button qualified fourth, four-tenths of a second behind Vettel, and Webber qualified fifth.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Massa, Rubens Barrichello, Schumacher, Rosberg and Petrov rounded out the top ten.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Kubica only managed 11th – missing out on the top ten for the only time in 2010 – having struggled with overall grip in the session.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Kamui Kobayashi was best of the Saubers in 12th, ahead of the German trio of Adrian Sutil, Nick Heidfeld and Nico Hülkenberg, with Vitantonio Liuzzi qualifying 16th.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The rest of the grid was made up by the Toro Rossos, the Lotuses, the Virgins and the Hispanias.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The conditions on the grid were dry before the race, the air temperature at 29 °C (84 °F), track temperature at 33 °C (91 °F); and no rain expected.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The race's formation lap commenced at 17:00 local time (UTC+4), with all 24 drivers getting away cleanly.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Vettel retained his pole position lead into the first corner, followed by Hamilton, with Button moving into third after Alonso made a slow start.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] At turn six, Schumacher tried to pass teammate Rosberg around the outside while battling for eighth.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The seven-time world champion spun his Mercedes, which meant he faced the rest of the oncoming field on track and was collected by Liuzzi, causing both drivers to retire on the spot and the safety car to be deployed.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] In order to aid any losses that a pit stop may have cost under normal racing conditions, six drivers – Rosberg, Petrov, Jaime Alguersuari, Bruno Senna, Lucas di Grassi and Christian Klien – made pit stops at the end of lap one, and rejoined the circuit between 17th and 22nd.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Racing resumed at the end of lap five when the safety car pulled into the pit-lane.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The top five remained static until the end of lap eleven.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Webber – who brushed the armco with the right-hand side of his car three laps previously – pitted after struggling for grip on the super-soft, option tyres.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] He rejoined the circuit 16th, and behind the early-stopping trio of Rosberg, Petrov and Alguersuari.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Four laps later, Alonso also brushed the Turn 19 barrier before pitting.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] He rejoined just in front of Webber, who had moved up the field steadily, and was running 13th – and set the race's fastest lap at the time – by the time Alonso pitted.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Vettel and Hamilton continued to set quicker lap times than their championship rivals, despite being on heavily worn option tyres compared to the fresher, hard tyres of Alonso and Webber.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] That pairing caught up with Petrov towards the end of lap 18, a battle that would go on until the race's conclusion, with the Renault driver having already stopped for tyres.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Five laps later, Alonso tried to overtake Petrov under braking for Turn 11 but had to back out of the manoeuvre, narrowly avoiding the back of the Renault.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] On the same lap, Hamilton pitted from second place.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Vettel pitted from the lead on the next lap, and rejoined the circuit comfortably ahead of Hamilton, but in second place behind Button, who had still to stop on track.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Hamilton had filtered back into the race in fifth position, behind Kubica and Kobayashi who were running similar strategies to Button out front.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] After passing Kobayashi, Hamilton closed in behind Kubica but found it hard to pass the Renault, akin to what Alonso had been suffering behind Petrov.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Despite having nearly 40 laps on the harder tyre, Kubica's pace was still of a substantial level to hold off the advances of Hamilton.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Button pitted on lap 39 to release Vettel back into the lead, holding a lead of nearly twelve seconds over Kubica.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Button rejoined in fourth place behind Kubica and Hamilton, with Kubica ever increasing his margin over Petrov and Alonso, who were running inside the points again in seventh and eighth respectively.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Kubica finally pitted on lap 46 from second place, and came back on track in fifth place, crucially ahead of teammate Petrov, Alonso and Webber; the latter pair seeing their championship chances dwindling with every passing lap.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] In clean air, Hamilton set the race's fastest lap on lap 47 – 1:41.274 – as he closed slightly on Vettel.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] No further passing attempts were made on track, and thus, Vettel led the race to the end, to take his fifth win of the season.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The McLarens of Hamilton and Button completed the podium ahead of Rosberg, the Renaults of Kubica and Petrov, Alonso and Webber.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Rounding out the points were Alguersuari and Massa, the Ferrari driver having never got ahead of his rival in 40 laps of battling.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] With the poor results of Alonso and Webber, Vettel claimed the championship to become the youngest Championship winner in the sport and became the first driver to simultaneously lead the championship for the first time, and as a result win the championship since James Hunt in 1976.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] His championship-winning margin was four points over Alonso; whom he would go ahead and replace in future at Ferrari, with Webber a further ten points behind in third.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] , summing up his race and his chances of his third championship disappearing.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Vettel's victory had left him "speechless", and expressed his delight at winning the Championship.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Hamilton praised his team for all their work during the season, stating that "we pushed very hard throughout the year, so a big thank to all the guys back home at the factory for not giving up.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Next year will be a better year." Button echoed Hamilton's comments about the work of his McLaren team, and summed up his first season with the team: "I would like to say a big thank you to the team.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] This is my first year with the team and I have had a great season.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] The **2010 Australian Grand Prix** (formally the **2010 Formula 1 Qantas Australian Grand Prix**) was a Formula One motor race held on 28 March 2010 at the Albert Park Circuit in Melbourne, Victoria, Australia.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] It was the second round of the 2010 Formula One World Championship.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] McLaren driver Jenson Button won the 58-lap race starting from fourth position.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Robert Kubica finished second for the Renault team and Ferrari driver Felipe Massa was third.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] The victory was Button's first of the season; the result moved him to third place in the World Drivers' Championship, two points behind Massa and a further four adrift of Alonso.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Hamilton dropped to fourth while Rosberg maintained fifth position.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] McLaren reduced the gap to Ferrari in the World Constructors' Championship to be sixteen points behind.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Mercedes increased their hold on third place, while Renault's strong result allowed them to tie with Red Bull for fourth place, with seventeen races left in the season.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] The Grand Prix was contested by twelve teams with two drivers each.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] The teams (also known as constructors) were Red Bull, Mercedes, McLaren, Ferrari, Renault, Williams, Force India, Sauber, Toro Rosso, Lotus, Hispania and Virgin.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Tyre supplier Bridgestone brought four different tyre types to the race: two dry compounds (soft "options" and hard "primes) and wet-weather compounds (intermediates and full wet).
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] The Soft compound was distinguished by a green stripe on the tyre's side-walls with the Wet compound tyre identified by a green line at the bottom of the tyre's central groove.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] As was the case for all of the 2010 Grands Prix, the rules stipulated that all cars should use both types of tyre during the course of the race unless the driver used any one of two wet-weather compounds.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Each driver was limited to eleven sets of dry tyres for the weekend.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] The circuit organisers installed a new combination kerb on the turn nine apex and artificial grass along with kerbs were extended downstream on the exits of the second and twelfth turns.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Before the race Ferrari driver Fernando Alonso led the World Drivers' Championship with 25 points, ahead of team-mate Felipe Massa (18 points) and McLaren driver Lewis Hamilton (15).
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Sebastian Vettel was fourth on twelve points and Nico Rosberg of Mercedes was fifth on ten points.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] In the World Constructors' Championship Ferrari were leading with 43 points, twenty-two points ahead of their rival McLaren in second.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Mercedes were in third place with 18 points with Red Bull a further two points adrift in fourth.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Force India were in fifth on two points.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Alonso had won the previous race in Bahrain with his team-mate Massa finishing second.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] The reigning Drivers' Champion Jenson Button who had won the 2009 Australian Grand Prix was pleased to be returning to Albert Park and set himself the target of finishing on the podium.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] After losing victory in Bahrain because of a faulty spark plug, Vettel was certain that Red Bull could challenge for the victory in Australia: "I think, coming out of Bahrain, we have a very good car.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Hamilton predicted that he would encounter less problems than in Bahrain and hoped he would have a good result in Melbourne.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] An issue concerning the start time of the race reemerged from the previous year.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] The start time was moved later in the day to allow European audiences to not get up early to view the event on television but it courted controversy as visibility was poor and it was retained for 2010.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Lotus driver Jarno Trulli suggested the race should be started one hour earlier, while Webber, the Grand Prix Drivers' Association director, said the reason was due to commercial pressure.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Some teams made modifications to their cars in preparation for the event.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] McLaren had to modify the opening of their diffusers following a rule clarification from the FIA.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] The team was also requested by the stewards in Bahrain to change the configuration of their front wing end-plates to a safer rounded shape for Australia.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Sauber became the first team to introduce their version of McLaren's F-duct system though the air was directed onto the main section of the body wing and the F-duct itself was positioned on the car's sidepods.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Three practice sessions were held before the Sunday race—two on Friday, and a third on Saturday.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] The Friday morning and afternoon sessions each lasted 90 minutes.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Before the practice sessions, the pit lane speed limit was lowered from 100 kilometres per hour (62 mph) to 60 kilometres per hour (37 mph) after a request was made from race director Charlie Whiting on safety grounds.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] In the first practice session which was held in dry weather conditions, Robert Kubica set the fastest time early in the session with a lap of 1:26.927, almost two-tenths of a second faster than Rosberg.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Button was third-fastest, ahead of Massa and Vettel.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Alonso, Hamilton, Sébastien Buemi, Vitaly Petrov and Vitantonio Liuzzi rounded out the session's top ten drivers.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Sauber driver Kamui Kobayashi caused the session to be suspended after forty minutes when he ran over a cone on the inside of turn eleven which tore off half his front wing and ran wide into the turn twelve gravel trap.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] A second suspension was caused after Kobayashi's second front wing broke off going into the third corner and debris was scattered across the circuit.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] In the second practice session which was marked by intermittent rain showers, Hamilton recorded the fastest lap of the day, a 1:25.801; his teammate Button was second quickest and battled his teammate for quickest lap-time.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Webber was third fastest, ahead of Michael Schumacher as both drivers took advantage of a drying track.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Adrian Sutil, Liuzzi, Rubens Barrichello and Rosberg rounded out the top ten.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Vettel lost control of the rear of his car and beached it in the turn six gravel trap in the final three minutes of the session.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] In the final practice session where traffic was heavy, Webber set the fastest lap of the weekend so far with a lap time of 1:24.719 which was set during the session's closing minutes.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Alonso (who was fastest for four minutes of the session after making changes to his rear suspension and front ride height) was two-tenths of a second slower in second.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Schumacher set the fastest time in the first sector to record the third fastest time.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] McLaren teammates Button and Hamilton were sixth and seventh.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Sutil, Massa and Liuzzi completed the top ten ahead of qualifying and were within one second off Webber's pace.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] The qualifying session held on Saturday afternoon was split into three parts.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] The second part of qualifying lasted 15 minutes and eliminated cars that finished in positions eleven to 17.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] The final session ran for ten minutes and determined pole position to tenth.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] The session was held in overcast conditions; the air and track temperature was 23 °C (73 °F).
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Vettel set the fastest time in all three sessions and achieved his second consecutive pole position of the season and his first at Albert Park with a time of 1:23.919 despite running wide after exiting a corner on his pole lap.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] He was joined on the front row of the grid by teammate Webber who set a lap time 0.116 seconds off Vettel's pace and lost the chance to take pole in the third session's closing minutes after he lost time in the middle sector but was quickest in the first and final sectors.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Alonso set a time of 1:24.111 to start from third place on the grid and was pleased on how qualifying went for himself.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Button lacked grip and had excessive oversteer which caused him to lose time and set the fourth quickest lap but was happy with the package of his car.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Massa struggled with getting his tyres up to the optimum temperature causing him to have no grip but managed to qualify fifth.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] The two Mercedes drivers used the soft compound tyres but only managed sixth and seventh positions with Rosberg ahead of Schumacher; Rosberg was disappointed after he made mistakes on his final run which cost him time while Schumacher also used the hard compound tyre and was caught up in traffic.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Barrichello took eighth and believed he could have set a faster lap because he encountered traffic during the third session.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Kubica pushed hard during the session as his car was not easy to drive and managed ninth.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Sutil rounded out the top ten but believed he could have done better as he struggled to get his soft compound tyres up to temperature after doing two runs in the third session.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Hamilton, who qualified eleventh, was the fastest driver not to advance into the final session.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] His best time of 1:25.184 was nearly 1.1 seconds slower than Vettel's pace in the second session.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] He was held up by traffic during the first run of the second session which meant he made an early pit stop for new tyres and to have a clear track.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] However Hamilton struggled with finding time in the final sector of the track.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Buemi took twelfth, with Liuzzi in thirteenth; the latter encountered a large amount of traffic in the final sector of the circuit despite going faster in the first two sectors.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Pedro de la Rosa pushed hard in qualifying to take 14th position with Nico Hülkenberg in the slower Williams 15th.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Kobayashi took 16th and Jaime Alguersuari started from 17th position.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Vitaly Petrov failed to move beyond the first qualifying session; the Renault driver qualified in 18th as he felt his car was not balanced correctly which meant he was unable to set good sector times on his final run.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] He also backed off in the final corners on his penultimate run of the session.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] The Lotus cars of Heikki Kovalainen and Trulli lined up in 19th and 20th respectively, with Trulli experiencing a problem with his seat which caused it to bounce in his car.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Virgin Racing drivers Timo Glock and Lucas di Grassi lined up in the eleventh row of the grid, with Hispania drivers Bruno Senna and Karun Chandhok qualifying on the final two positions on the grid in 23rd and 24th.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] The fastest lap in each of the three sessions is denoted in bold.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] The conditions on the grid were wet before the race; the air temperature ranged between 26 and 29 °C (79 and 84 °F) and the track temperature ranged from 24 to 28 °C (75 to 82 °F).
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] All cars started on the intermediate compound tyre.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Virgin Racing nominated to start Glock and di Grassi from pit lane after replacing the fuel collectors on their cars because issues in qualifying forced them to run with more fuel than would be ideal.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Trulli attempted to start the race from the pit lane after his Lotus suffered a hydraulic pump failure on the grid, but the team were unable to rectify the problem and Trulli did not start.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] When the race started, Vettel maintained his advantage heading into the first corner while Massa made a fast start to slot into second position ahead of Webber.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Kubica had an excellent getaway, rising from ninth to fourth position by the end of the first lap.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Hamilton made up three positions over the same distance.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] At the first corner Button's front left wheel made contact with Alonso's right rear tyre, causing the Spanish driver to spin and dropped to 22nd position.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Schumacher was collected by Alonso and sustained a broken front wing.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Further around the lap, Kobayashi damaged his front wing from contact with another car at turn three, which became detached going into turn six and made heavy contact with the side of Hülkenberg and Buemi.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] The incident prompted the deployment of the safety car.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Schumacher drove into the pit lane to fit a new front wing.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Racing resumed at the end of lap four when the safety car pulled into the pit-lane with Vettel leading Massa.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Kubica attempted to pass Webber but the Australian maintained his position by moving to the outside.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Schumacher attempted to pass di Grassi for 19th position on the same lap. di Grassi managed to retake the position from Schumacher by driving around the outside of Ascari corner, but Schumacher got ahead of di Grassi on the pit straight.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] At the end of the first racing lap, Vettel led Massa by 1.1 seconds, who in turn was followed by Webber, Kubica, Rosberg, Button, Hamilton, Sutil, Barrichello and Petrov.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Hamilton passed his teammate Button for sixth at turn three on lap six.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Senna stopped on the circuit to retire with a hydraulic failure on the same lap.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Massa slowed on the next lap which caused Webber to move into second.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Button called his team to bring out slick tyres and endured a large amount of water to enter the pit lane on lap seven.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Button slid off the circuit at turn three, while Vettel had a 1.2 second over teammate Webber by the eighth lap.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] The track started to dry which resulted in most of the field pitting for soft dry tyres.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Vettel made a pit stop from the lead on lap nine.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Webber took over the lead for one lap before his pit stop on the tenth lap.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] He went off at the first corner, and fell behind Massa.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Petrov missed the braking point for Whiteford corner on lap ten and spun off into the gravel trap which caused his car to become beached and retired.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Sutil briefly took over the lead until he made a pit stop on lap twelve and got out of his car to retire because he lost power in his engine.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Thus, Vettel regained the first position as he began to slowly pull away from Button who was 1.7 seconds behind Vettel on lap 13 with Kubica a further two seconds adrift in third.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Alonso had moved into tenth position by lap 13 and gained a further after he overtook de la Rosa at turn nine on the same lap.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Alonso passed Barrichello for eighth on the 14th lap and set a new fastest lap on the following lap, a 1:31.573.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Hamilton and Webber passed Alonso for fifth and sixth positions at the start of lap 16.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Webber attempted to defend fifth place from Hamilton but went wide into the gravel trap at turn three and fell down to eighth.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Massa immediately overtook Hamilton around the outside on the same lap.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Hamilton started to battle Massa (who had graining on his right-rear tyre) for fifth position with Webber and Alonso starting to close the gap to the two drivers.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Massa slid his car at turn 16 at the end of lap 21 which allowed Hamilton to pass Massa on the inside at Brabham corner although Hamilton sustained minor damage to his front wing.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Hamilton defended Massa's attempt to pass him at Whiteford corner, while Alonso slowed which allowed Webber to pass him.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Hamilton overtook Rosberg on the outside of turn eleven.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Vettel had sparks coming from his left-front wheel and a large amount of vibrations built up in his car.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] This caused Vettel to lose torque drive between the front left axle and wheel, and spun into the gravel trap at Ascari corner on lap 26.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Vettel's retirement promoted Button into the lead.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Rosberg attempted to retake fourth from Hamilton at Ascari corner but was unable to because of the presence of yellow-flags.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Webber passed Massa for fifth position at Whiteford corner two laps later. di Grassi drove to his garage to retire with an issue with his car's hydraulics on lap 29.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Hamilton closed up on Kubica by the same lap; Hamilton attempted to overtake Kubica while in traffic but Kubica fended off Hamilton's attempt.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Hamilton feigned passing manoeuvres at the Brabham and Whiteford corners with the latter attempt resulting in Hamilton losing time to Kubica and fell back in front of Rosberg.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Webber made a pit stop for soft compound tyres on lap 33, while Hamilton tried another pass on Kubica on the back straight but Kubica closed the door on Hamilton.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Rosberg made his pit stop for tyres one lap later and came out level with Webber as Rosberg exited the pit lane, but Webber's extra momentum allowed him to move ahead of Rosberg.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Despite going fastest overall in the first and second sectors of the track after making a pit stop on lap 35, Hamilton went wide at Ascari corner on lap 37 which allowed Webber to briefly move ahead of Hamilton before the McLaren driver regained the position.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Hamilton and Webber began to close on Alonso at the rate of two seconds a lap after setting a new fastest lap of the race, a 1:28.591 on lap 40 while Massa started to close the gap to Kubica. di Grassi rejoined the race on lap 39 but returned to the pit lane two laps later.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Glock made a pit stop and his mechanics retired him from the race on the 45th lap because a camber shim on his car was loose and it caused the left rear suspension to move around.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Hamilton caught Alonso on lap 49 but was unable to pass the Ferrari driver because Hamilton struggled with tyre degradation.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Schumacher dived up the inside to attempt an overtake Alguersuari for eleventh place at Ascari corner on lap 56 and the two drivers wheels made contact before Schumacher got ahead at the Stewart corner.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Hamilton attempted to pass Alonso around the outside at Ascari corner on the same lap but Alonso closed the door on Hamilton.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Webber took advantage but missed his braking point because his front wing stopped producing downforce which prevented him from reducing his speed and locked his tyres.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] He collided one of Hamilton's rear tyres, sending both drivers into the gravel trap.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Both drivers managed to continue and Webber drove into the pit lane to replace his front wing.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Button had maintained his lead upfront and crossed the start/finish line after 58 laps to win his first race of the 2010 season and his second consecutive Australian Grand Prix.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Kubica finished second 12 seconds behind Button, with Massa in third.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Alonso held off Rosberg in the final laps to finish fourth.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] The organisers of the race invited actor John Travolta to wave the chequered flag.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] The top three drivers appeared on the podium to collect their trophies and in a later press conference.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Button said it was "very special" that he won in his second race for the McLaren team as it taken him time to get used to his car.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] He felt that his confidence was increasing and hoped something similar would occur in the following race of the year.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Kubica said that he had not been expecting to finish on the podium and thanked the effort of his Renault team for helping him achieving his second-place result.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] He also said that his team were not with the pace of the top three teams but felt the race was "a good example of not giving up".
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Massa's third-place finish was his best at the Melbourne Grand Prix and said it was fantastic that he had secured one second and third place podium finishes in the season's first two events.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] He praised his team for selecting a strategy of not making a pit stop after 20 laps of the race had been completed and felt it was good for all of the top three finishers.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Hamilton was disappointed not to have finished in a higher position and accused Webber of "not thinking" following the collision between the two drivers on the 57th lap.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Although Webber apologised to Hamilton he was issued with a reprimand by the stewards.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] He said that he wanted to achieve a podium finish but that it was a "tough day" for the Red Bull team and had been determined to not give up.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Vettel believed he could have won the race had he not been affected by a car failure saying that Red Bull were pushing and trying to do the best they could and wanted to ensure that he clinched victory in the Malaysian Grand Prix.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Alonso declared himself to be very happy with his fourth-place result despite being involved in the first lap collision.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] He said that he was not thinking about Massa at the time but scoring points but claimed he had the perfect car to win the race.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] The result meant Alonso remained the leader of the Drivers' Championship with 37 points with his teammate Massa reducing the deficit to four points.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Button's victory meant he moved into third place with 31 points and Hamilton fell down to fourth.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Rosberg remained in fifth position on 20 points.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] In the Constructors' Championship Ferrari remained the leader although McLaren cut their lead to be 16 points behind.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Kubica's second place allowed Renault to tie Red Bull for fourth place with 18 points each, with seventeen races remaining in the season.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-australian-grand-prix] Drivers who scored championship points are denoted in bold.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] The **2010 Bahrain Grand Prix** (formally the **2010 Formula 1 Gulf Air Bahrain Grand Prix**) was a Formula One motor race held on 14 March 2010 at the Bahrain International Circuit, Sakhir, Bahrain.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] It was the seventh Bahrain Grand Prix and the opening round of the 2010 Formula One season.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] It was the first time since 2006 that Bahrain had hosted the opening round and the race took place on a lengthened layout of the track.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] The race was won by Fernando Alonso, his first as a Ferrari driver and his first F1 victory overall since the 2008 Japanese Grand Prix.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] His new teammate, Felipe Massa ensured a good start to the year for the team by finishing second.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] McLaren driver Lewis Hamilton completed the podium by finishing in third position.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] All of the race had been led by polesitter and Red Bull driver Sebastian Vettel, until lap 34 when a power issue forced him to concede the lead to Alonso.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] This meant that he was eventually overtaken by Massa and Hamilton too, meaning that he finished in fourth place.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Vettel's teammate, Mark Webber qualified sixth before finishing the race in eighth place.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Michael Schumacher's first race of his return to Formula One for the Mercedes team resulted in him finishing sixth, one place behind teammate Nico Rosberg.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Reigning world champion Jenson Button completed his first race for the McLaren team by finishing seventh.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] It was also the Grand Prix debut of Nico Hülkenberg, who finished fourteenth for his team Williams.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] The three new teams—Lotus, Hispania and Virgin—did not have a very successful debut race.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Their six cars occupied the last six places in qualifying, and only one, the Lotus of Heikki Kovalainen, finished the race, although Jarno Trulli's Lotus was also classified in last place.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] As a consequence of the race, Fernando Alonso and Ferrari led their respective championships with maximum points.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] The extended 'Endurance Layout' of the Bahrain International Circuit proved unpopular with drivers and teams and as of 2025 has never been used by the series again.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] New drivers Nico Hülkenberg, Karun Chandhok, Bruno Senna, Lucas di Grassi and Vitaly Petrov also take part in their maiden races.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Hülkenberg joined Williams, Petrov joined Renault and di Grassi became part of the Virgin team, while Hispania had an all-rookie line-up of Senna and Chandhok.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Petrov became Russia's first ever Formula One World Championship driver; Chandhok became India's second following Narain Karthikeyan; Senna is a nephew of the legendary three-time Formula One world champion Ayrton Senna.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] 2009 World Drivers' Champion Jenson Button made his debut for McLaren after changing teams from 2009 Constructors' Champion team Brawn in November 2009.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Seven-time World Champion Michael Schumacher made his return to Formula One with Mercedes, Felipe Massa returned for Ferrari after his head injury at the 2009 Hungarian Grand Prix, and Timo Glock returned with the Virgin team following his accident at the 2009 Japanese Grand Prix.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] All the previous winners of the event were present: Jenson Button won the 2009 Bahrain Grand Prix, with the Ferrari pair of Fernando Alonso and Felipe Massa both being two-time winners at this circuit.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] The race also saw a return to the banning of refueling of the cars during the race, a practice which had been allowed since the 1994 Formula One season.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Additionally a new points scoring system to decide the World Drivers' Championship was implemented, the most radical revamp of the system since the formation of the World Championship in 1950.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] At 24 drivers and cars, this was the first time more than 22 cars had started Grand Prix since the 1995 Japanese Grand Prix (which also had 24 starters) and the largest event entry list since the 1997 Australian Grand Prix weekend where 24 cars were entered (but only 21 cars started that race).
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] The race was also the first to feature a revised stewards' panel under new FIA regulations, featuring a former Formula One driver.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] The driver in Bahrain was four-time World Champion Alain Prost.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Adrian Sutil set the fastest time for the Force India team in the first session of free practice on Friday morning.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Fernando Alonso (Ferrari) was second, ahead of Robert Kubica (Renault), Felipe Massa in the other Ferrari, and the two McLaren drivers, Jenson Button and Lewis Hamilton.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] On his return to Formula One, Michael Schumacher set the tenth-fastest time for Mercedes, two positions behind teammate Nico Rosberg.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Of the new teams, both Lotus drivers and Timo Glock set times, but Lucas di Grassi did not complete a full lap in the second Virgin car.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] The Hispania team was still completing its two chassis when the session started, but Bruno Senna was able to complete two installation laps before it ended.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] In session 2 of free practice, Nico Rosberg set the fastest time, with Hamilton in second and Schumacher came third.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Senna was struggling to match the pace of the fastest GP2 Asia Series drivers, but eventually did so, four seconds off the pace of the Virgins.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] In the Saturday free practice session, Alonso in the Ferrari set the fastest time of 1:54.099, 0.269 seconds faster than Nico Rosberg in the Mercedes.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Hispania's Karun Chandhok failed to participate in the practice session due to a hydraulic problem.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Elsewhere, the Virgin of Glock lost its left-front wheel in the middle of the session, with the problem being attributed to an under-torqued airgun.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] The first qualifying session saw the six drivers from the three new teams eliminated, with Timo Glock – the fastest of the newcomers – 2.7 seconds adrift of Jaime Alguersuari in eighteenth and the only driver from the established teams to be eliminated.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Despite a crippling hydraulics problem that saw him unable to take part in any of the free practice sessions, Hispania's Karun Chandhok was able to qualify in 24th and last place with a lap time ten seconds slower than the fastest driver, Ferrari's Fernando Alonso.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Reigning World Champion Jenson Button narrowly avoided elimination in the second qualifying period, pushing former Brawn GP teammate Rubens Barrichello out of the top ten and into elimination.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Barrichello's Williams teammate Nico Hülkenberg was also eliminated, as were both Saubers of Pedro de la Rosa and Kamui Kobayashi, the second Toro Rosso of Sébastien Buemi, Force India's Vitantonio Liuzzi and rookie driver Vitaly Petrov in the Renault.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Red Bull's Sebastian Vettel took pole late in the third session, edging out the Ferraris of Massa and Alonso, with 2008 World Champion Lewis Hamilton in fourth.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Mercedes's Nico Rosberg and seven-time World Champion Michael Schumacher were fifth and seventh respectively, with Sebastian Vettel's Red Bull teammate Mark Webber splitting them.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Jenson Button could only manage eighth place, while ninth and tenth were taken by Robert Kubica and Adrian Sutil in the remaining Renault and Force India.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] The first corner of the first lap saw Mark Webber's engine release copious amounts of oil smoke, triggering a sequence of events that saw Adrian Sutil and Robert Kubica spin around and fall to the back of the field.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] The first lap was otherwise clean, with Sebastian Vettel quickly converting his pole position into the race lead.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Fernando Alonso got past teammate Felipe Massa, to get second, and both Mercedes drivers also gained a place, with Nico Rosberg fourth ahead of Lewis Hamilton, and Michael Schumacher beating Mark Webber to sixth spot.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] There was little position-changing otherwise, with Vitaly Petrov in the second Renault the biggest mover, up to eleventh from seventeenth on the grid.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] It was a race of attrition, with the first major incident of the race being the retirement of Hispania's Karun Chandhok, who, after just a handful of laps in qualifying, hit a bump he did not know existed and retired with a damaged front wing.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Virgin Racing's Lucas di Grassi joined him on the sidelines shortly thereafter when his Virgin VR-01's hydraulics — a chronic problem throughout the off-season — gave up.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Fellow rookie Nico Hülkenberg was lucky to avoid a similar fate to Chandhok when he missed a corner on the run down to turn seventeen and skipped over the circuit.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Renault later clarified the issue as being an unanticipated mechanical fault on both cars that was traced back to Petrov's preference for a lower ride height than teammate Kubica who went unscathed.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Timo Glock in the second Virgin also retired after losing third and fifth gears, while Bruno Senna's debut for Hispania ended when his engine overheated at the end of the main straight.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] The six drivers retired during the first seventeen laps.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] At the front, Vettel and the two Ferraris quickly pulled out a sizeable gap to the rest of the field.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] The first round of pit stops also proved to be the only round of stops, with Vettel stretching out enough of a lead to prevent the Ferraris from leap-frogging them.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Elsewhere, good work from the McLaren crew allowed both their drivers to gain a place in the stops; Hamilton on Rosberg, and Jenson Button on Webber.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] The list of retirements grew on lap 23 when Pedro de la Rosa in the second BMW Sauber was also struck by a hydraulic issue.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Vettel continued to lead comfortably, two seconds ahead of Alonso and a further three ahead of Massa.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] However, he began to noticeably slow down during the latter part of the race due to a problem that was later identified within the team as a problem with a spark plug, and was quickly passed by the two Ferraris and Hamilton, and spent the rest of the race trying to hold Rosberg at bay.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Alonso went on to win the race, joining Juan Manuel Fangio, Giancarlo Baghetti, Mario Andretti, Nigel Mansell and Kimi Räikkönen as the only men to win their first Grand Prix in a Ferrari.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Massa finished second on his return to full-time racing after his injury at the 2009 Hungarian Grand Prix.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Hamilton completed the podium, while Vettel successfully fended Rosberg off long enough to salvage fourth.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Schumacher followed his teammate home for sixth, with Button seventh, Webber eighth, Vitantonio Liuzzi placing ninth and Barrichello claiming the final point on offer.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Kubica recovered from his first-corner spin to claim eleventh while Sébastien Buemi and Jarno Trulli also retired; Buemi's Toro Rosso was struck by electrical issues, while Trulli added his name to the growing list of drivers taken down by hydraulics issues.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] As they each retired having completed 46 laps, they were classified as finishers as they completed ninety percent of the winner's race distance.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] Heikki Kovalainen finished fifteenth in the second Lotus, meaning that Lotus became the only entrant of the new teams to have a car finish the race.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] There was criticism after the race of the "new" Formula One, with it being echoed by Formula One personalities.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] The new section of the circuit used by Formula One for the first time also drew criticism from both drivers and fans alike, with most claiming the added corners offered little in the way of passing opportunities.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] For the next Bahrain Grand Prix in 2012, Formula One would revert to using the original Grand Prix Circuit.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-bahrain-grand-prix] – Both Sébastien Buemi and Jarno Trulli were classified as they had completed 90% of the winner's race distance.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The **2010 Belgian Grand Prix** (officially the **2010 Formula 1 Belgian Grand Prix**) was a Formula One motor race held before a crowd of 60,000 spectators at the Circuit de Spa-Francorchamps in Francorchamps, Wallonia, Belgium, on 29 August.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] It was the 13th round of the 2010 Formula One World Championship and the 55th Belgian Grand Prix held as part of the Formula One World Championship.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] McLaren's Lewis Hamilton won the 44-lap race after starting from second position.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Red Bull's Mark Webber was second ahead of Robert Kubica's third-placed Renault, his final podium in F1.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] It was Hamilton's third victory of the season and the 14th of his career.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Webber, who led the World Drivers' Championship with a four-point lead over Hamilton and his team Red Bull led the World Constructors' Championship, achieved the sixth pole position of his career by setting the fastest lap in qualifying but started slowly and immediately lost the lead to Hamilton.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The Grand Prix was slowed by two safety car deployments due to a collision between the Williams car of Rubens Barrichello and Ferrari's Fernando Alonso on the first lap and another accident for Alonso on the 38th lap.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Hamilton led throughout in variable weather, despite running into a gravel trap on lap 35, and finished 1.5 seconds ahead of Webber.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Kubica took his last podium by finishing third after overshooting the entry to his pit lane box late in the race.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The result returned Hamilton to the top of the World Drivers' Championship standings with 182 championship points, three ahead of the previous leader Webber in second.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Webber's teammate Vettel remained in third despite coming 15th after colliding with Button and sustaining a left-rear puncture from contact with Vitantonio Liuzzi's Force India car.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] McLaren lowered Red Bull's World Constructors' Championship lead to one championship point with Ferrari third with six races left in the season.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The 2010 Belgian Grand Prix was the 13th of the 19 events in the 2010 Formula One World Championship, and the 55th World Championship edition of the race.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] It was held at the 19-turn 7.004 km (4.352 mi) Circuit de Spa-Francorchamps, located in Francorchamps, Wallonia, Belgium, on 29 August.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Formula One tyre supplier Bridgestone brought the soft and medium dry compounds and the intermediate and full wet-weather tyres to the race.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] La Source turn had a larger area of artificial grass and a 50 mm (2.0 in) kerb installed at the corner to deter competitors from transgressing track limits.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] After winning the preceding Hungarian Grand Prix, Red Bull's Mark Webber led the World Drivers' Championship with 161 championship points, ahead of Lewis Hamilton of McLaren with 157 championshippoints and Webber's teammate Sebastian Vettel with 151 championship points.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Hamilton's teammate Jenson Button was fourth with 147 championship points and Ferrari's Fernando Alonso was fifth with 141 championship points.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] With 312 championship points, Red Bull led the World Constructors' Championship followed by McLaren in second with 304 championship points and the third-placed Ferrari with 238 championship points.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Mercedes were fourth with 132 championship points and Renault were fifth with 106 championship points.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The race was the first after a four-week gap between races that includes a mandatory two-week shut-down for all teams.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] With 20 races or 15 races there is probably more room for mistakes – but with seven to go every single races is probably more important." Hamilton said he was confident of better pace for the rest of the season and wanted to win at Spa-Francorchamps.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] His teammate Button believed the next two races would be consequential for the championship but said they would better suit his McLaren.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Some teams modified their cars for better efficiency on the track's straights.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Ferrari introduced a new rear wing with less downforce on Felipe Massa's F10 car for qualifying and the race.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The team also added a modified diffuser and floor to maximise the F10's performance within FIA compliance restricting the size of the car's lower surface to reduce the downforce generated.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Red Bull altered the RB6's brake discs for extra ballast around the car and improved performance and McLaren installed a new front wing on Button's MP4-27 vehicle to improve airflow and downforce.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Renault introduced a version of McLaren's F-duct tool to their R30 car activated by the driver's left hand and directed air to the main section of the rear wing instead of the flap.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The team was impressed at the F-duct's performance during practice and retained the tool for the rest of the meeting.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Williams introduced new front and rear wings for their FW32 cars and Force India added a new floor to their vehicles.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Having driven one of its cars since the British Grand Prix three races earlier, Hispania Racing opted to retain Sakon Yamamoto in lieu of Karun Chandhok, whom the press anticipated would return to drive for the squad following the mid-season interval.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Paul di Resta, Force India's reserve and test driver, did not enter the first practice session because the team wanted its race drivers Vitantonio Liuzzi and Adrian Sutil to become acclimatised with a revised aerodynamic bodywork.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] There were three practice sessions held in accordance with the 2010 regulations, two 90-minute sessions on Friday morning and afternoon and one 60-minute session on Saturday morning.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Heavy rain fell on the circuit at about midnight before the first session.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Although the track was wet, a decent level of grip was reported as some drivers aquaplaned when the rain briefly increased in intensity and lightning came approximately 50 minutes in; the rain abated with 20 minutes left.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Alonso lapped fastest at 2:01.223 at mid-point before improving to a 2:00.797 late on.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Hamilton, Renault's Robert Kubica, Vettel, Sutil, Button, Webber, Kamui Kobayashi of Sauber, Williams' Rubens Barrichello, and Mercedes' Michael Schumacher made up positions two through ten.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The second session commenced on a damp circuit which gradually dried up bar a small rain shower early on.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Drivers used wet-weather tyres before switching to the dry compounds.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Alonso led with the day's fastest lap, a 1:49.032, ahead of Sutil, Hamilton, Kubica, Massa, Vettel, Button, Pedro de la Rosa for Sauber, Barrichello and De la Rosa's teammate Kamui Kobayashi in positions two to ten.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Due to the damp conditions, some drivers ventured off the track during the session.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Liuzzi lost control under braking for Rivage chicane but was able to return to the pit lane for a new front wing.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Virgin's Timo Glock lost control of his car on a white line and crashed sideways into the barrier at Liège corner.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The session was stopped for ten minutes by the stewards for a safety hazard limiting dry track running.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Children were reportedly climbing the catch fence on track grounds, forcing FIA race director Charlie Whiting to drive the safety car and do an inspection.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] While the session restarted with four minutes left, a malfunctioning red light delayed on-track action, requiring marshals to wave a green flag to resume proceedings.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] More overnight rain showers made the track damp by the start of the final session but slick tyres were used after 20 minutes.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Conditions remained dry enough for drivers to go faster until a downpour fell on the circuit with 15 minutes remaining and caught out some participants.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] With a 1:46.106 lap being almost three seconds quicker than Friday's best time, Webber led from Hamilton, Vettel, Button, Kubica, Alonso, Massa, Sutil, Williams' Nico Hülkenberg and Kobayashi.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Vettel stopped his car at the pit lane entry with his car stuck in gear due to an air box fault prompting his team to instruct him to switch off the engine as a precaution.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] A group of marshals moved Vettel's car into the pit lane for retrieval by his team.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Saturday afternoon's qualifying session was split into three parts.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The first session ran for 20 minutes, eliminating cars that finished 18th or lower.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The second session was 15 minutes long, eliminating cars that finished 11th to 17th.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The final ten-minute session determined pole position to tenth.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Cars in the final session were not allowed to change tyres before the start of the race, using the set with which they set their quickest lap times.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Qualifying commenced in clear weather before rain showers fell on parts of the circuit, making the surface uneven and catching some drivers out.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The rain soon abated and the circuit quickly dried up before light rain fell again at the third session's end.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Webber positioned himself for space and driving on the circuit at its driest, for his first pole position since the Turkish Grand Prix, his fifth of the season and the sixth of his career with a 1:45.778 lap set late in the third session.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] It was the 12th time in 13 races Red Bull had pole position.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Webber was joined on the grid's front row by Hamilton whose first timed lap was on old soft tyres with his second on a new set of tyres before the rain fell.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Kubica in third did not set a second timed lap in the final session because a fuel feed fault cut out his car entering the pit lane and requiring mechanics to push his car into the garage for the rest of qualifying.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Errors on each of his third session laps left Vettel fourth.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Button took fifth by saving a set of soft tyres despite losing time through an error at La Source turn and being circumspect at Fagnes corner.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Massa, sixth, altered his rear wing for better straightline speed but had less grip in the turns halfway through the lap.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Barrichello qualified seventh for his 300th Grand Prix on the hard compound tyre having depleted his soft tyre allocation in the first two sessions.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Sutil, eighth, had one timed lap on one set of soft compound tyres and Hülkenberg in ninth was on worn soft tyres.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Alonso, 10th, lost a plethora of time running wide on the damp La Source corner; he used less front wing angle and an old rear wing.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Schumacher was the fastest driver not to progress to the final session in 11th.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] His teammate Rosberg in 12th lacked grip on a wet-weather set-up and had to slow when he came across the Toro Rosso car of Sébastien Buemi.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Toro Rosso's Jaime Alguersuari slowed on the slippery turns 13 and 14 on his final timed lap and was 13th ahead of Liuzzi in 14th.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Heikki Kovalainen advanced to the second session for the second time in 2010 since the Malaysian Grand Prix and qualified his Lotus 16th.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Lotus' Jarno Trulli, 18th, made contact with the right-rear of Lucas di Grassi's out of control Virgin Racing vehicle at Stavelot turn.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] A tyre strategy error and going wide into the gravel on the wet track left Kobayashi 19th.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Hispania Racing driver Bruno Senna was 20th and his teammate Yamamoto 21st following a tyre strategy error and Yamamoto being impeded by a slower car.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] De la Rosa in 22nd lost control of the rear of his car at Rivage turn and struck the wall.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Di Grassi, 23rd, set no lap time after his collision with Trulli.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Vitaly Petrov lost control of his Renault on dry tyres on a damp kerb exiting Rivage corner and spun into the inside barrier backwards.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The session was stopped for six minutes so that marshals could move his car off the track.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] A total of five drivers received grid penalties post-qualifying.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Schumacher was demoted ten places for forcing Barrichello close to the concrete wall at the Hungarian Grand Prix.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] His teammate Rosberg lost five places for changing his car's gearbox to one that had not been used unused for four races.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Buemi was demoted three positions because he was deemed by the race stewards to have transgressed the sporting regulations by blocking Rosberg in the second session.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The stewards penalised Glock five positions for illegally blocking Yamamoto in the first session.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] De la Rosa incurred the loss of ten places for changing his car's engine between qualifying and the race for the ninth time in the season, exceeding the eight allowed maximum engine switches.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The fastest lap in each of the three sessions is denoted in **bold**.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The 44-lap race started before 60,000 spectators at 14:00 local time.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] A 60 per cent chance of rain showers between 14:00 and 15:00 local time were forecast, and at the start, weather conditions were overcast, although some rain had fallen during the support races and there was a large build-up of rain showers to the west of Spa-Francorchamps.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The air temperature was between 14 and 16 °C (57 and 61 °F) and the track temperature from 17 to 21 °C (63 to 70 °F).
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The rain showers observed in the morning's support events altered the level of grip, and tyre strategy had the potential to effect the final finishing order according to Sarah Holt of BBC Sport.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Cars were allowed to be changed slightly following the FIA's declaration of a change in climatic conditions post-qualifying.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Every driver bar Barrichello, Rosberg and Schumacher began on the soft compound tyre.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Before the start, Massa was observed by amateur video footage posted on the internet to have transgressed sporting regulation by being slightly out of position on the grid.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] He was not punished since neither the marshals, teams or the automatic jump start system relayed the fact to Whiting for him to impose a jump start penalty on Massa.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] At the start, Hamilton took the lead from a slow-starting Webber into the La Source hairpin with Kubica second and Button third.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Webber allowed the engine revolutions to fall too low, causing his car's Renault engine to go into anti-stall mode and falling to sixth.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Hamilton held off Kubica on the outside in the braking zone of Les Combes turn as Button failed to pass Kubica.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Sutil clung onto Webber's slipstream and overtook him on the straight for sixth before losing the place by running wide into Les Combes corner.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] A rain shower began to fall towards the conclusion of the first lap.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The rain shower made the back of the track damp through Blanchimont corner and the conditions caused several drivers to run wide at the Bus Stop chicane due to a loss of grip braking for the turn.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Button attempted to pass Kubica on the outside but sustained left front wing damage affecting its aerodynamic balance as it became apparent several drivers could not turn into the chicane and drove onto the run-off tarmac.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Barrichello was unable to stop his car in time in the greasy conditions despite his braking early and struck the side of Alonso's eighth-placed car.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Alonso was able to make a pit stop for intermediate tyres as well as other drivers but Barrichello retired with car damage.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Button followed the chicane's contours and fell behind Vettel but held off Massa by braking very late for the La Source hairpin.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] He thus drew to the inside of Vettel and overtook him for third.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] In the second lap, Hamilton experienced a minor loss of control of his car through Eau Rouge turn but retained the lead.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Kubica used his F-duct system but ran wide onto the outside run-off area, promoting Button to second.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Vettel was forced wide by the rejoining Kubica and protested over the radio.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Webber passed Massa on the inside for fifth before the safety car was dispatched at lap two's conclusion, as a consequence of the first lap accident between Alonso and Barrichello as Barrichello's car was being removed from the circuit.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The leaders remained on the track as three drivers lower down the order made pit stops for intermediate tyres.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The rain abated on lap three as a blue sky began to appear through the clouds.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The safety car was withdrawn at the conclusion of lap three and racing resumed with Hamilton leading his teammate Button.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Hamilton ran wide at the La Source hairpin and blocked his teammate Button from passing him for the lead, while Vettel used the restart to pass Kubica for third at the same hairpin.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Sutil's higher straightline speed moved him past Hülkenberg for seventh to nullify an earlier illegal pass by the latter on the former at the Bus Stop chicane.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Button's handling difficulties caused by front wing damage allowed his teammate Hamilton to pull away from the rest of the field to be 4.8 seconds ahead by lap seven.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] On lap six, Senna, nursing front wing damage, drove slowly into the pit lane to retire with rear-left suspension failure that caused him to spin.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Vettel drew close to Button as he went faster uphill through Eau Rouge but him hitting his rev limiter on the Kemmel straight into the braking area for Les Combes corner and the effectiveness of the McLaren's F-duct system allowing for a longer gear ratio and a tailwind kept Button ahead.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] During lap 11, Petrov overtook Rosberg on the outside for ninth into Les Combes turn and put the latter wide.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Having noticed Petrov's overtake on his teammate, Schumacher passed Rosberg on the outside for tenth eapproaching Malmedy corner, with Schumacher's rear wheel and Rosberg's front wing endplate colliding.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] That same lap, Vettel got a run on the conservatively braking Button on the inside into the Bus Stop chicane.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Vettel suddenly switched to the outside line and lost control of his car by hitting a bump on the damp circuit as he was unable to correct an opposite lock at high speed.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] He struck the left-hand sidepod on Button's car, exposing its radiator and causing Button's retirement.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Vettel entered the pit lane for a replacement front wing and fell to 12th position.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The accident promoted Kubica to second and Webber to third.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The stewards informed the Red Bull team the collision would be investigated and decided to impose a drive-through penalty on Vettel on the 20th lap.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Vettel was informed of the penalty by his race engineer, and took it on the next lap.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Sutil was the first of the leaders to make a scheduled pit stop for the medium compound tyres on lap 22.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Red Bull responded by calling Webber into the pit lane on the next lap, followed in turn by Kubica and Massa on lap 24.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Kubica rejoined ahead of Webber and held off the latter into Les Combes turn.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] On lap 25, Hamilton made his first pit stop and retained the lead.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Sutil overtook Schumacher uphill into Les Combes turn for fifth on the lap.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] On lap 26, Vettel overtook Liuzzi at the Bus Stop chicane but Liuzzi's right-front wing endplate punctured Vettel's left-rear tyre.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Vettel was unable to enter the pit lane and had to do a full lap before stopping for the soft compound tyres and fell to 20th; Liuzzi immediately made a pit stop for a front wing replacement.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] On lap 31, Hamilton led Kubica by 11.2 seconds, who in turn, was 2.3 seconds ahead of Webber in third.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] As Alonso challenged Kobayashi for eighth, light rain again began to fall on lap 34.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] At first, the track was slightly wet and made drivers unsure when to make pit stops for wet-weather tyres.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Drivers began to make pit stops for wet-weather tyres on lap 35.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] On that lap, Hamilton was unable to slow enough in the slippery conditions due to tyre locking and slid into the gravel trap at Rivage corner.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Hamilton made light contact with the wall with his front wing but had enough traction to get himself out of the gravel and return to the track in the lead.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The first three drivers entered the pit lane at the lap's end.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Kubica had a problematic pit stop: he overshot his pit box through braking too late and glanced the legs of a team member because he was distracted with the switches on his steering wheel for car adjustments.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Kubica's delay moved Webber to second as Hamilton retained the lead.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] On lap 38, the safety car was deployed for a second time because of an accident requiring marshal intervention.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Alonso ran wide on the paint marking the outside kerb exiting Les Combes turn and into Malmedy corner and lost control of his car.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] He veered across the track to the inside and crashed into the tyre wall, fracturing his front-right suspension before stopping in the circuit's centre.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The crash forced Alonso to retire from the race.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The safety car was withdrawn at the conclusion of lap 40 for four laps of racing.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Hamilton led Webber in second and Kubica in third.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Into Les Combes turn, Rosberg overtook Kobayashi and then his teammate Schumacher on the outside for sixth by forcing him wide on the inside kerbs.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Alguersuari cut the Bus Stop chicane and passed Liuzzi for tenth on lap 42.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] At the front, Hamilton took his third win of the season and the 14th of his career, at an average speed of 207.509 km/h (128.940 mph).
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Webber followed 1.571 seconds later in second and Kubica finished in third place.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Massa secured fourth, holding off Sutil in fifth.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The Mercedes pair of Rosberg and Schumacher finished sixth and seventh following the team's decision to keep their drivers on track for longer and were just more than a second ahead of eighth-placed Kobayashi.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Petrov was ninth and Algersuari provisionally tenth.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Liuzzi came 11th with De la Rosa 12th after a late race error sent him into the gravel at Curve Paul Frere corner when closing up on Petrov.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Buemi was provisionally 13th after sustaining diffuser damage and a tyre puncture when another driver struck the rear of his car.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Hülkenberg, 14th, had faulty throttle control causing him to spin multiple times and requiring him to make an extra pit stop.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Vettel was 15th, with Kovalainen after a poor start caused by his engine's anti-stall system activating and Di Grassi 16th and 17th.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Di Grassi stated Kovalainen overtook him off the circuit at Les Combes corner but no punishments were issued by the stewards.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Glock in 18th lost performance on a set of full-wet tyres before the second rain shower and ran a new front wing after demolishing a brake marker board on lap one.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Trulli and Yamamoto were the final classified finishers.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The top three drivers appeared on the podium to collect their trophies and spoke to the media in a later press conference.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Hamilton described it as "a very, very tough race" for himself and said the victory "absolutely" made up for two years prior, adding: "At the end it was just about nursing the car home and bringing it back in one piece.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Vettel apologised for the collision with Button that eliminated the latter from the race.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] He said: "Obviously it was not my intention to destroy his race or mine.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The moment Robert [Kubica] got close behind I knew that he could pass us on the straight because we are not the fastest on the straight.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] I'm guessing he [Vettel] thought I was going to pull from the left and he went on the inside.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] But he got a little rattled and didn't know which way to go." Martin Whitmarsh, the McLaren team principal, commented on the collision: "It was not what you would expect to see in F1 – more reminiscent of junior formulae.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] A drive-through seemed a pretty light punishment to me.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] It was a bit of a strange mistake I have to say.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] I realise it was not intentional but it was a pretty strange one really." Red Bull team principal Christian Horner argued Button braked early and that the accident was unintentional while motorsport advisor Helmut Marko said Vettel could not fellow Button for longer since the latter was slower.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] After reviewing video evidence and the change in the weather, the race stewards imposed no penalty or a caution for the first lap collision between Alonso and Barrichello, which they deemed "a racing incident".
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Because I wasn't following the pit wall in terms of position, I was watching the weather all the time.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The stewards added 20 seconds to Alguersuari's overall race time in lieu of a drive-through penalty after deeming him to have illegally cut the Bus Stop chicane to pass Liuzzi for tenth on lap 42.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The penalty demoted Alguersuari to 13th and elevated Liuzzi to the final points-scoring place of 10th.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] The FIA opened an investigation into how Massa began just ahead of his grid slot without the error being detected in time.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Massa said his short stature prevented him from observing the lines well: "I was a little bit outside, and that was it." The result returned Hamilton atop World Drivers' Championship with 182 championship points.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Webber fell to second with 179 championship points as his teammate Vettel remained third with 151 championship points.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] With a respective 147 and 141 championship points, Button and Alonso were fourth and fifth.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] McLaren with 329 championship points lowered Red Bull's (330) World Constructors' Championship lead to one point.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] With 250 championship points, Ferrari were third with Mercedes with 146 championship points and Renault with 123 championship points fourth and fifth with six races left in the season.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2010-belgian-grand-prix] Drivers who scored championship points are denoted in **bold**.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] The **2016 Spanish Grand Prix** (formally known as the **Formula 1 Gran Premio de España Pirelli 2016**) was a Formula One motor race held on 15 May 2016 at the Circuit de Barcelona-Catalunya in Montmeló, Spain.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] The race was the fifth round of the 2016 FIA Formula One World Championship, and marked the forty-sixth running of the Spanish Grand Prix as a round of the Formula One World Championship.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] It was the twenty-sixth time that the race has been held at the circuit.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Nico Rosberg was the defending race winner and entered the round with a forty-three-point lead over teammate Lewis Hamilton in the Drivers' Championship.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Their team, Mercedes, held an eighty-one point lead over Ferrari in the Constructors' Championship.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Hamilton took pole position during qualifying, ahead of teammate Rosberg and Red Bull's Daniel Ricciardo.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Max Verstappen won the race upon his début for his new team Red Bull, having swapped his Toro Rosso seat with Daniil Kvyat ahead of the event.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] At the age of 18 years and 228 days, Verstappen became the youngest ever winner and the youngest driver to score a podium finish of a Formula One race, breaking the previous records held by Sebastian Vettel.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] In the process he also became the first Dutchman to win a Grand Prix and the first Grand Prix winner born in the 1990s.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Daniil Kvyat and Max Verstappen traded places ahead of the race.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Verstappen joined Red Bull Racing while Kvyat returned to Scuderia Toro Rosso.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Red Bull's team principal Christian Horner explained the driver swap with Verstappen's talent, saying that the 18-year-old Dutchman and Daniel Ricciardo had the potential to become Formula One's best driver pairing.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Furthermore, he stressed that Verstappen's move to Red Bull would tie him to the team for the foreseeable future.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Daniil Kvyat meanwhile expressed surprise at the decision, saying during Thursday's press conference that he was "shocked" by his demotion, stressing that Red Bull did not give him a "real explanation".
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Following problems with his power unit in both the Chinese and Russian Grand Prix, Lewis Hamilton received a redesigned MGU-H unit, in a bid to solve the troubles which hampered him earlier.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] However, Mercedes were unable to guarantee that the problem would not appear again.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] With Spain being the first race in Western Europe, and a mid-season test coming up after the race, many teams introduced their first major car updates for the Grand Prix.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Mercedes ran a new front wing with a "more pointy" nose during first free practice.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Other changes were made to the engine cover and the rear wing.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] McLaren made more significant changes to their MP4-31, most notably on the front wing, which Sky Sports commentator Ted Kravitz called the "most intricate front wing I've ever seen".
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Force India updated their VJM09 to improve airflow.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] According to the team, they were looking for improved driveability rather than faster lap times.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Renault introduced a new chassis for Jolyon Palmer.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] More significantly, the French manufacturer debuted a new version of their power unit for both their works team and Red Bull at the two-day test following the race.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] All other teams except for Sauber also made changes to their cars, with the Swiss team continuing their financial struggles.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] They also announced that they would be forced to miss the mid-season test, being unable to field a development driver, with regulations demanding that two out of four test days be driven by young driver talents.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Both Sauber and Haas were allowed to use the updated version of Ferrari's 2016 power unit, which the works team had already used in Russia two weeks earlier.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Going into the weekend, Nico Rosberg led the Drivers' Championship, having taken the maximum number of 100 points from the first four races.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Lewis Hamilton followed in second with 57 points, while Kimi Räikkönen was third with 43 points.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Daniel Ricciardo followed in fourth, ahead of Sebastian Vettel.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] In the Constructors' standings, Mercedes was first with 157 points, 81 points clear of second-placed Ferrari.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Behind them, Red Bull led fourth-placed Williams by just six points.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Sole tyre supplier Pirelli brought the hard, medium and soft tyres to the event, the first time this season to feature the orange hard tyres.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] As per the regulations of the 2016 season, every driver had to set aside one set each of the two hardest compounds for the race and one set of the soft tyres for Q3 (should they advance).
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] The drivers had freedom of what other compounds they chose for the remaining ten out of thirteen sets.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Per the regulations for the 2016 season, two 90-minute practice sessions were held on Friday and another 60-minute session was held before qualifying on Saturday.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] The Ferrari drivers, Sebastian Vettel and Kimi Räikkönen, set the pace in the first session, both on the soft tyre compound.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] The Mercedes drivers Rosberg and Hamilton followed, albeit on the medium compound, recording more timed laps than their rivals.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Both Red Bull cars followed in fifth and sixth, with Daniel Ricciardo faster than new teammate Max Verstappen.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Valtteri Bottas was seventh for Williams, two places ahead of teammate Felipe Massa, who at one point spun out at turn five.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Upon his return to Toro Rosso, Daniil Kvyat was unable to match the pace of his teammate Carlos Sainz Jr., ending up half a second behind him.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Esteban Ocon made his first free practice appearance of the season for Renault, replacing Jolyon Palmer, but was unable to set a timed lap.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] He suffered a tyre failure, caused by debris on the track.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Force India's Sergio Pérez managed only nine laps as he spent much of the session in the pit lane after smoke emerged from the rear of his car.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Mercedes topped the time sheets in the second session, now switching to the soft compound tyres as well, with Nico Rosberg two and a half-tenths of a second clear of Kimi Räikkönen, while Lewis Hamilton was third fastest, more than seven-tenths off Rosberg's time.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Räikkönen's running was interrupted for a while when he was called back into the pitlane to investigate a fuel system problem, but was able to get back out.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Fernando Alonso was seventh fastest for McLaren, but needed a replacement of his car's plank after running wide over artificial grass surrounding the track.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] His teammate, Jenson Button, also experienced problems, having to stop at the end of the pitlane early in the session with an electrical issue.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Renault's problem from the first session continued: Jolyon Palmer, back in his car in place of Ocon, suffered a tyre failure on the start-finish straight, bringing out red flags in the process.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Renault and tyre supplier Pirelli were left puzzled over the failure, as in this incident, no sign of a cut from debris was found.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Nico Rosberg was again fastest in the third practice session on Saturday morning, setting a time of 1:23.078 on his first timed run, a time that stood until the end of the session.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Hamilton was second, 0.126 seconds off, followed by Sebastian Vettel just two-hundredths of a second behind him.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] In fourth place, Max Verstappen was faster than teammate Ricciardo for the first time, who finished fifth, ahead of Räikkönen.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Upon beginning his preparation laps for qualifying, Rosberg had to come back into the garage, as a sensor on his car was malfunctioning.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] The team was capable of repairing the damage and he went back out for the final minutes of practice.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Sergio Pérez was satisfied with the eighth fastest time, saying that the car had improved "everywhere" following the updates it had received.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Qualifying consisted of three parts, 18, 15 and 12 minutes in length respectively, with six drivers eliminated from competing after each of the first two sessions.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] In the first part of qualifying (Q1), Nico Rosberg set a time of 1:23.002, the fastest of the weekend up to that point, two-tenths of a second ahead of teammate Hamilton.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Manor and Sauber occupied the back rows of the grid.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Felipe Massa's first lap was seven-tenths of a second slower than the one from his teammate Bottas and as he was unable to set another timed lap, he became the surprise elimination in Q1, behind Jolyon Palmer, who was dropped into 17th place by a late improvement from Jenson Button.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] In Q2, it was Hamilton who came out on top, exactly six-tenths of a second ahead of Rosberg.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Verstappen was third fastest, ahead of Ricciardo in fifth.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Kimi Räikkönen had to abandon his first fast lap after running wide in turn four, but later set a time good enough for fourth.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Meanwhile, Sebastian Vettel recorded just one timed lap, saving a set of tyres and was sixth.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] On his return to Toro Rosso, Kvyat was eliminated in 13th place, while teammate Sainz went through to Q3.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Sergio Pérez advanced as well, demoting his teammate Hülkenberg into elimination in the process, who would line up eleventh on the grid.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Joining him on the sidelines for Q3 were Jenson Button in twelfth, with Romain Grosjean, Kevin Magnussen and Esteban Gutiérrez lining up behind Kvyat.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Lewis Hamilton and Nico Rosberg were the first out in Q3.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Hamilton's early sector times put him on course to a new fastest lap of the weekend, but a brake lockup at turn ten ruined his lap and tyres.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Nico Rosberg made no such mistake and claimed provisional pole position.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] As the two Ferrari drivers struggled to find pace, Max Verstappen claimed second place for the time being, before the drivers went out for their second laps.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Lewis Hamilton's second flying lap bested Rosberg's time by almost three-tenths of a second, and saw him take the fifty-second pole of his career.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] The two Red Bull cars of Ricciardo and Verstappen followed, with Räikkönen and Vettel for Ferrari in fifth and sixth respectively, both more than a second behind Hamilton.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Valtteri Bottas was best of the rest ahead of Sainz, Pérez and Alonso.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] It was the first appearance in Q3 for McLaren since they resumed their association with Honda in 2015.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] At the start, Nico Rosberg got around the outside of Hamilton in turn one, while Räikkönen lost positions due to a slow getaway.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Sebastian Vettel got past Verstappen, but was immediately repassed on the approach to turn four.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] At the front of the race, coming out of turn three, Hamilton tried to retake the position from Rosberg.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] As the latter defended his position, Hamilton went off the track and spun and they collided at turn 4, ending the race of both Mercedes drivers.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] The collision resulted in a safety car period, with the order standing: Ricciardo, Verstappen, Sainz, Vettel and Räikkönen.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] The safety car came in at the end of lap four.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Vettel got past Sainz on lap eight and Räikkönen tried to follow suit two laps later, but was forced off track into turn two.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] He completed the move one lap later at the same spot.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Sainz and Button were the first to come into the pit lane for new tyres on lap 12, followed by race leader Ricciardo one lap later, making Verstappen the first Dutchman to lead a Grand Prix, before he came in another lap later.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] When Vettel made a pit stop on lap 16, he emerged third behind the two Red Bull drivers, all on the medium compound tyre.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] By lap 20, Sebastian Vettel was closing the gap to the two Red Bulls ahead of him, coming within three seconds of Verstappen.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] On lap 22, Nico Hülkenberg retired when his power unit caught fire and he had to stop on the sidelines.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] While Massa had fought from 18th on the grid into tenth, his teammate Bottas was lying fifth by lap 25, ahead of Sainz.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] On lap 28, Ricciardo was again the first of the front runners to pit, taking on the soft compound.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Vettel came in two laps later, making the same choice in tyres.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] This left Verstappen to lead Kimi Räikkönen, as it emerged that both would run on a different strategy, pitting only twice in contrast to the three stopping Vettel and Ricciardo.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] On lap 34, the gap between the two leaders was 2.1 seconds, before Verstappen came in on the following lap.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Räikkönen responded one lap later, emerging behind Verstappen.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] On lap 39, Vettel came in for his third and final stop, while Ricciardo stayed out for another four laps.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] When he returned to the track, he was behind Vettel, but on fresher tyres.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] While Räikkönen closed on Verstappen at the front, Fernando Alonso's home race ended on lap 47, pulling over to the side of the track at turn three.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Räikkönen managed to get into the one-second window to activate the drag reduction system (DRS), as Vettel was eight seconds behind him with Ricciardo closing on him in fourth place.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] By lap 57, Ricciardo was close enough to use DRS as well, but unable to pass.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Three laps later, Ricciardo made an attempt at overtaking into turn one, but braking too late left him running wide, allowing Vettel back through.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] As the front runners lapped backmarkers, Kvyat, after scoring the first fastest lap for himself and Toro Rosso, overtook Gutiérrez for tenth place.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Two laps from finish, Ricciardo suffered a puncture and was forced to pit, but retained fourth place ahead of Bottas.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] On the last lap, Renault drivers Kevin Magnussen and Jolyon Palmer collided, but both made it to the finish.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] As Verstappen crossed the finish line, he became the youngest ever and first Dutch race winner in Formula One.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] At the podium interviews, conducted by singer Plácido Domingo, Verstappen expressed delight about a "great race", crediting his team with giving him a good car.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Kimi Räikkönen said that while he was happy for Verstappen, he was disappointed not to have won.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] He blamed the lack of downforce while following as the reason why he had been unable to pass Verstappen.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Vettel congratulated the winner as well, but lamented that his different strategy had not worked out in his favour.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] During the post-race press conference, Räikkönen stressed that had anyone offered the team two podium positions after their poor performance in qualifying, they would have taken it "happily".
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Fourth placed Ricciardo expressed bitterness over Red Bull's decision to switch him to a three-stop strategy, which eventually lost him a podium position, saying: "I'm a bit devastated.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] A big part of me is happy the team are on winning form but it's hard to celebrate".
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] His team later explained their decision, declaring that they had focused their strategy on Vettel, who they had considered the biggest threat.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Vettel had been 21 years and 2 months at the time.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Verstappen also became the youngest driver to lead at least one lap of a Grand Prix, again overcoming a record set by Vettel, at the 2007 Japanese Grand Prix.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Verstappen also was the first driver born in the 1990s to win a Grand Prix.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] He received considerable praise after the race, with Sky Sports F1's David Croft saying that he "has shown he has everything to be a world champion".
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] His father Jos Verstappen, himself a former Grand Prix driver, declared that he considered his son a better driver than himself, as race wins had eluded him during his own career in the sport.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] French sport newspaper *L'Équipe* declared Verstappen to be "already a great" and "in the big leagues".
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Verstappen was also the first Dutchman to win a race, with the Netherlands becoming the 22nd country to produce a race winner.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] He was the tenth different winner of the Spanish Grand Prix in as many past editions.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Following their collision, Hamilton and Rosberg were summoned to the stewards after the race but neither received a penalty, as the stewards rated their crash as a racing incident, with no driver in particular to blame.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] It emerged that Rosberg had chosen the wrong engine mode for the start, being down on power which led to Hamilton going for a passing manoeuvre.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] However, Rosberg remained convinced that he had done nothing wrong, saying: "I made it very clear I wasn't going to leave any space on the inside and I was very surprised he went for the gap".
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] While Hamilton apologised to the team after the incident, he refused to accept blame for it.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Opinions about the incident varied: While Mercedes's executive chairman Niki Lauda blamed Hamilton for the crash, former F1 driver Anthony Davidson said on Sky Sports F1 that Rosberg's move was "very aggressive".
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Three-time world champion Jackie Stewart said after the race that Mercedes should fine Hamilton for the crash: "Hamilton is to blame.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] You don't go for it on the first lap." Mercedes's head of motorsport Toto Wolff stressed after the race that the team would continue to let their drivers race against each other freely, a decision praised by former world champion Alain Prost.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] While Rosberg said after the race that he contemplated having a talk with Hamilton about the situation, Mercedes later decided that they did "not need clear-the-air talks".
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] However, it later emerged that the pair did have a conversation about the incident before the next race in Monaco, which, according to Hamilton, was marked by "pure respect".
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] It was Mercedes's first double retirement since the 2011 Australian Grand Prix, and the first time they failed to score a point since the 2012 United States Grand Prix, ending a 62-race long streak, the third longest in Formula One history.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] For his last lap collision with teammate Jolyon Palmer, Kevin Magnussen received a ten-second time penalty, dropping him one place to 15th.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] He also received two penalty points to his licence.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Carlos Sainz received a reprimand from the stewards for leaving the pit lane one minute before it was allowed.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] He escaped a more severe penalty because he stopped shortly afterwards, thereby not gaining an advantage.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Upon his return to Toro Rosso, Daniil Kvyat recorded the first fastest lap of his career, and the first for the Italian team in their 190th Grand Prix.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] With 100 points from the first four races, Nico Rosberg remained on top of the Drivers' Championship, while Hamilton's retirement dropped him behind Räikkönen, who now trailed Rosberg by 39 points, four points ahead of Hamilton.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Sebastian Vettel and Daniel Ricciardo were level on points with 48, while Verstappen's victory moved him into sixth on 38.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] In the Constructors' standings, Mercedes retained their lead on 157 points, but Ferrari closed the gap to 48 points, with Red Bull in third on 94.
[src:2016-spanish-grand-prix/2016-spanish-grand-prix] Toro Rosso moved ahead of Haas into fifth, while Force India took seventh from McLaren.
